{"title_page": "Kamalini Ramdas", "text_new": "{{short description|British academic}}\n{{Infobox economist\n| name             = Kamalini Ramdas\n| image       =\n| image_size       =\n| caption    =\n| birth_date       =\n| birth_place      =\n| death_date       =\n| death_place      =\n| nationality      = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| institution      = [[London Business School]] <br> [[University of Virginia]] <br> [[University of Texas at Austin]]\n| field            = [[Operations Management]] <br> [[Healthcare]]<br>[[Management Science]]\n| alma_mater       = [[University of Pennsylvania]] (PhD, 1995) <br> [[Delhi University]] (B.S., 1986)\n}}\n\n'''Kamalini Ramdas''' is a Professor of Management Science and Operations and Deloitte Chair in Innovation & Entrepreneurship at [[London Business School]], with expertise in the areas of [[innovation]], [[entrepreneurship]], and [[healthcare|operations management]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.london.edu/faculty-and-research/faculty/profiles/r/ramdas-k|title=Kamalini Ramdas|website=London Business School|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> Ramdas' research examines innovative approaches, including service innovation,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hbr.org/2012/12/four-ways-to-reinvent-service-delivery|title=Four Ways to Reinvent Service Delivery|last=Ramdas|first=Kamalini|date=2012-12-01|work=Harvard Business Review|access-date=2019-09-10|last2=Teisberg|first2=Elizabeth|issue=December 2012|issn=0017-8012|last3=Tucker|first3=Amy L.}}</ref> operational innovation,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ramdas|first=Kamalini|last2=Saleh|first2=Khaled|last3=Stern|first3=Steven|last4=Liu|first4=Haiyan|date=2017-08-02|title=Variety and Experience: Learning and Forgetting in the Use of Surgical Devices|journal=Management Science|volume=64|issue=6|pages=2590\u20132608|doi=10.1287/mnsc.2016.2721|issn=0025-1909|url=https://lbsresearch.london.edu/748/1/Ramdas%20et%20al.%20Hips_Variety_2016_Forthcoming.pdf}}</ref> and business model innovation,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://innovationroundtable.com/summit/kamalini-ramdas/|title=Kamalini Ramdas|website=Innovation Roundtable\u00ae Summit 2019|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> to accelerate [[Business value|value creation]] in various service and manufacturing industries.\n\n==Career==\nKamalini Ramdas earned her BS in [[mathematics]] from [[St. Stephen's College, Delhi|St. Stephen's College]], [[Delhi University]] in 1986, M.S. in [[operations research]] from [[University of Delaware]] in 1989, and PhD in [[operations management]] from the [[Wharton School]] of [[University of Pennsylvania]] in 1995. Prior to joining London Business School in 2008, Ramdas served as Associate Professor of Business Administration at [[University of Virginia Darden School of Business]]. She was also on the faculty of [[McCombs School of Business]] of [[The University of Texas at Austin]].\n\nAt London Business School, Ramdas is a Professor of Management Science and Operations and Deloitte Chair in Innovation & Entrepreneurship. She also serves as the Subject Area Chair of [[Management science|Management Science]] & [[Operations research|Operations]].\n\nShe is currently President of the Manufacturing and Service Operations Management Society (MSOM), one of the largest societies of the [[Institute for Operations Research and the Management Sciences]] (INFORMS).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://connect.informs.org/msom/about-us/officers|title=Officers - MSOM Society|website=connect.informs.org|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\n==Academic work==\nRamdas is known for her work in [[innovation]], [[entrepreneurship]], and [[operations management]]. Her work has found applications in a wide range of industries, including [[healthcare]], [[telecommunication]], [[Consumer Packaged Goods|consumer packaged goods]], and assembled products.\n\nIn particular, she is a pioneering scholar in innovation in [[healthcare]] delivery, known internationally for her work in shared medical appointments.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ramdas|first=Kamalini|last2=Darzi|first2=Ara|date=2017-03-23|title=Adopting Innovations in Care Delivery \u2014 The Case of Shared Medical Appointments|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=376|issue=12|pages=1105\u20131107|doi=10.1056/NEJMp1612803|issn=0028-4793|pmid=28328325|hdl=10044/1/46086}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Rethinking interactions: Kamalini Ramdas at TEDxLondonBusinessSchool|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6fPUIXJzZew|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> In 2011, she was invited to present her work on innovation in healthcare delivery at the [[World Economic Forum]] in [[Davos]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.london.edu/lbsr/learning-from-davos|title=Learning from Davos|website=London Business School|language=en|access-date=2019-09-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.weforum.org/people/kamalini-ramdas/|title=Kamalini Ramdas|website=World Economic Forum|access-date=2019-09-25}}</ref>\n\nShe serves or has served on the editorial board of major operations management journals, including [[Management Science (journal)|''Management Science'']], ''[[Manufacturing & Service Operations Management]]'', [[IEEE Technology and Engineering Management Society|''IEEE Transactions on Engineering Management'']], and [[Production and Operations Management|''Productions and Operations Management'']].\n\n==Publications==\nAccording to [[Google Scholar]], Ramdas' 10 most widely cited papers are:\n*{{cite journal|last1=Fisher|first1=Marshall|last2=Ramdas|first2=Kamalini|last3=Ulrich|first3=Karl|title=Component Sharing in the Management of Product Variety: A Study of Automotive Braking Systems|journal=Management Science|volume=45|issue=3|year=1999|pages=297\u2013315|issn=0025-1909|doi=10.1287/mnsc.45.3.297}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Ramdas|first1=Kamalini|title=Managing Product Variety: An Integrative Review and Research Directions|journal=Production and Operations Management|volume=12|issue=1|year=2009|pages=79\u2013101|issn=1059-1478|doi=10.1111/j.1937-5956.2003.tb00199.x}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Ramdas|first1=Kamalini|last2=Spekman|first2=Robert E.|title=Chain or Shackles: Understanding What Drives Supply-Chain Performance|journal=Interfaces|volume=30|issue=4|year=2000|pages=3\u201321|issn=0092-2102|doi=10.1287/inte.30.4.3.11644}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Ramdas|first1=Kamalini|last2=Sawhney|first2=Mohanbir S.|title=A Cross-Functional Approach to Evaluating Multiple Line Extensions for Assembled Products|journal=Management Science|volume=47|issue=1|year=2001|pages=22\u201336|issn=0025-1909|doi=10.1287/mnsc.47.1.22.10667}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Laseter|first1=T.M.|last2=Ramdas|first2=K.|title=Product Types and Supplier Roles in Product Development: An Exploratory Analysis|journal=IEEE Transactions on Engineering Management|volume=49|issue=2|year=2002|pages=107\u2013118|issn=0018-9391|doi=10.1109/TEM.2002.1010879|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/228c6f2f9aa33d8837f6f27db18a2afe8c88aa65}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Fisher|first1=Marshall|last2=Ramdas|first2=Kamalini|last3=Zheng|first3=Yu-Sheng|title=Ending Inventory Valuation in Multiperiod Production Scheduling|journal=Management Science|volume=47|issue=5|year=2001|pages=679\u2013692|issn=0025-1909|doi=10.1287/mnsc.47.5.679.10485}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Ramdas|first1=Kamalini|last2=Randall|first2=Taylor|title=Does Component Sharing Help or Hurt Reliability? An Empirical Study in the Automotive Industry|journal=Management Science|volume=54|issue=5|year=2008|pages=922\u2013938|issn=0025-1909|doi=10.1287/mnsc.1070.0791}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Ramdas|first1=Kamalini|last2=Fisher|first2=Marshall|last3=Ulrich|first3=Karl|title=Managing Variety for Assembled Products: Modeling Component Systems Sharing|journal=Manufacturing & Service Operations Management|volume=5|issue=2|year=2003|pages=142\u2013156|issn=1523-4614|doi=10.1287/msom.5.2.142.16073|url=https://repository.upenn.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1328&context=mgmt_papers}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Parker|first1=Chris|last2=Ramdas|first2=Kamalini|last3=Savva|first3=Nicos|title=Is IT Enough? Evidence from a Natural Experiment in India's Agriculture Markets|journal=Management Science|volume=62|issue=9|year=2016|pages=2481\u20132503|issn=0025-1909|doi=10.1287/mnsc.2015.2270|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/9df0f5a4bd215bb69084386248366c7805b46c82}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Atkinson|first1=Scott E.|last2=Ramdas|first2=Kamalini|last3=Williams|first3=Jonathan W.|title=Robust Scheduling Practices in the U.S. Airline Industry: Costs, Returns, and Inefficiencies|journal=Management Science|volume=62|issue=11|year=2016|pages=3372\u20133391|issn=0025-1909|doi=10.1287/mnsc.2015.2302|url=https://lbsresearch.london.edu/67/1/delays-arw_2014-10-27.pdf}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n*\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kamalini Ramdas}}\n[[Category:Academics of the London Business School]]\n[[Category:Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Management scientists]]\n[[Category:British business theorists]]\n[[Category:British women academics]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British academic}}\n{{Infobox economist\n| name             = Kamalini Ramdas\n| image       =\n| image_size       =\n| caption    =\n| birth_date       =\n| birth_place      =\n| death_date       =\n| death_place      =\n| nationality      = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| institution      = [[London Business School]] <br> [[University of Virginia]] <br> [[University of Texas at Austin]]\n| field            = [[Operations Management]] <br> [[Healthcare]]<br>[[Management Science]]\n| alma_mater       = [[University of Pennsylvania]] (PhD, 1995) <br> [[Delhi University]] (B.S., 1986)\n}}\n\n'''Kamalini Ramdas''' is a Professor of Management Science and Operations and Deloitte Chair in Innovation & Entrepreneurship at [[London Business School]], with expertise in the areas of [[innovation]], [[entrepreneurship]], and [[healthcare|operations management]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.london.edu/faculty-and-research/faculty/profiles/r/ramdas-k|title=Kamalini Ramdas|website=London Business School|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> Ramdas' research examines innovative approaches, including service innovation,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hbr.org/2012/12/four-ways-to-reinvent-service-delivery|title=Four Ways to Reinvent Service Delivery|last=Ramdas|first=Kamalini|date=2012-12-01|work=Harvard Business Review|access-date=2019-09-10|last2=Teisberg|first2=Elizabeth|issue=December 2012|issn=0017-8012|last3=Tucker|first3=Amy L.}}</ref> operational innovation,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ramdas|first=Kamalini|last2=Saleh|first2=Khaled|last3=Stern|first3=Steven|last4=Liu|first4=Haiyan|date=2017-08-02|title=Variety and Experience: Learning and Forgetting in the Use of Surgical Devices|journal=Management Science|volume=64|issue=6|pages=2590\u20132608|doi=10.1287/mnsc.2016.2721|issn=0025-1909|url=https://lbsresearch.london.edu/748/1/Ramdas%20et%20al.%20Hips_Variety_2016_Forthcoming.pdf}}</ref> and business model innovation,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://innovationroundtable.com/summit/kamalini-ramdas/|title=Kamalini Ramdas|website=Innovation Roundtable\u00ae Summit 2019|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> to accelerate [[Business value|value creation]] in various service and manufacturing industries.\n\n==Career==\nKamalini Ramdas earned her BS in [[mathematics]] from [[St. Stephen's College, Delhi|St. Stephen's College]], [[Delhi University]] in 1986, M.S. in [[operations research]] from [[University of Delaware]] in 1989, and PhD in [[operations management]] from the [[Wharton School]] of [[University of Pennsylvania]] in 1995. Prior to joining London Business School in 2008, Ramdas served as Associate Professor of Business Administration at [[University of Virginia Darden School of Business]]. She was also on the faculty of [[McCombs School of Business]] of [[The University of Texas at Austin]].\n\nAt London Business School, Ramdas is a Professor of Management Science and Operations and Deloitte Chair in Innovation & Entrepreneurship. She also serves as the Subject Area Chair of [[Management science|Management Science]] & [[Operations research|Operations]].\n\nShe is currently President of the Manufacturing and Service Operations Management Society (MSOM), one of the largest societies of the [[Institute for Operations Research and the Management Sciences]] (INFORMS).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://connect.informs.org/msom/about-us/officers|title=Officers - MSOM Society|website=connect.informs.org|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\n==Academic work==\nRamdas is known for her work in [[innovation]], [[entrepreneurship]], and [[operations management]]. Her work has found applications in a wide range of industries, including [[healthcare]], [[telecommunication]], [[Consumer Packaged Goods|consumer packaged goods]], and assembled products.\n\nIn particular, she is a pioneering scholar in innovation in [[healthcare]] delivery, known internationally for her work in shared medical appointments.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ramdas|first=Kamalini|last2=Darzi|first2=Ara|date=2017-03-23|title=Adopting Innovations in Care Delivery \u2014 The Case of Shared Medical Appointments|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=376|issue=12|pages=1105\u20131107|doi=10.1056/NEJMp1612803|issn=0028-4793|pmid=28328325|hdl=10044/1/46086}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Rethinking interactions: Kamalini Ramdas at TEDxLondonBusinessSchool|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6fPUIXJzZew|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> In 2011, she was invited to present her work on innovation in healthcare delivery at the [[World Economic Forum]] in [[Davos]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.london.edu/lbsr/learning-from-davos|title=Learning from Davos|website=London Business School|language=en|access-date=2019-09-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.weforum.org/people/kamalini-ramdas/|title=Kamalini Ramdas|website=World Economic Forum|access-date=2019-09-25}}</ref>\n\nShe serves or has served on the editorial board of major operations management journals, including [[Management Science (journal)|''Management Science'']], ''[[Manufacturing & Service Operations Management]]'', [[IEEE Technology and Engineering Management Society|''IEEE Transactions on Engineering Management'']], and [[Production and Operations Management|''Productions and Operations Management'']].\n\n==Publications==\nAccording to [[Google Scholar]], Ramdas' 10 most widely cited papers are:\n*{{cite journal|last1=Fisher|first1=Marshall|last2=Ramdas|first2=Kamalini|last3=Ulrich|first3=Karl|title=Component Sharing in the Management of Product Variety: A Study of Automotive Braking Systems|journal=Management Science|volume=45|issue=3|year=1999|pages=297\u2013315|issn=0025-1909|doi=10.1287/mnsc.45.3.297}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Ramdas|first1=Kamalini|title=Managing Product Variety: An Integrative Review and Research Directions|journal=Production and Operations Management|volume=12|issue=1|year=2009|pages=79\u2013101|issn=1059-1478|doi=10.1111/j.1937-5956.2003.tb00199.x}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Ramdas|first1=Kamalini|last2=Spekman|first2=Robert E.|title=Chain or Shackles: Understanding What Drives Supply-Chain Performance|journal=Interfaces|volume=30|issue=4|year=2000|pages=3\u201321|issn=0092-2102|doi=10.1287/inte.30.4.3.11644}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Ramdas|first1=Kamalini|last2=Sawhney|first2=Mohanbir S.|title=A Cross-Functional Approach to Evaluating Multiple Line Extensions for Assembled Products|journal=Management Science|volume=47|issue=1|year=2001|pages=22\u201336|issn=0025-1909|doi=10.1287/mnsc.47.1.22.10667}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Laseter|first1=T.M.|last2=Ramdas|first2=K.|title=Product Types and Supplier Roles in Product Development: An Exploratory Analysis|journal=IEEE Transactions on Engineering Management|volume=49|issue=2|year=2002|pages=107\u2013118|issn=0018-9391|doi=10.1109/TEM.2002.1010879|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/228c6f2f9aa33d8837f6f27db18a2afe8c88aa65}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Fisher|first1=Marshall|last2=Ramdas|first2=Kamalini|last3=Zheng|first3=Yu-Sheng|title=Ending Inventory Valuation in Multiperiod Production Scheduling|journal=Management Science|volume=47|issue=5|year=2001|pages=679\u2013692|issn=0025-1909|doi=10.1287/mnsc.47.5.679.10485}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Ramdas|first1=Kamalini|last2=Randall|first2=Taylor|title=Does Component Sharing Help or Hurt Reliability? An Empirical Study in the Automotive Industry|journal=Management Science|volume=54|issue=5|year=2008|pages=922\u2013938|issn=0025-1909|doi=10.1287/mnsc.1070.0791}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Ramdas|first1=Kamalini|last2=Fisher|first2=Marshall|last3=Ulrich|first3=Karl|title=Managing Variety for Assembled Products: Modeling Component Systems Sharing|journal=Manufacturing & Service Operations Management|volume=5|issue=2|year=2003|pages=142\u2013156|issn=1523-4614|doi=10.1287/msom.5.2.142.16073|url=https://repository.upenn.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1328&context=mgmt_papers}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Parker|first1=Chris|last2=Ramdas|first2=Kamalini|last3=Savva|first3=Nicos|title=Is IT Enough? Evidence from a Natural Experiment in India's Agriculture Markets|journal=Management Science|volume=62|issue=9|year=2016|pages=2481\u20132503|issn=0025-1909|doi=10.1287/mnsc.2015.2270|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/9df0f5a4bd215bb69084386248366c7805b46c82}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Atkinson|first1=Scott E.|last2=Ramdas|first2=Kamalini|last3=Williams|first3=Jonathan W.|title=Robust Scheduling Practices in the U.S. Airline Industry: Costs, Returns, and Inefficiencies|journal=Management Science|volume=62|issue=11|year=2016|pages=3372\u20133391|issn=0025-1909|doi=10.1287/mnsc.2015.2302|url=https://lbsresearch.london.edu/67/1/delays-arw_2014-10-27.pdf}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n*\n\n{{DE