{"title_page": "1298 Imperial election", "text_new": "The 1298 election really was the enthronement of Albert of Austria as outcome of the deposition of Adolf of Nassau. The electors probably did not plan from the beginning to depose the king, but as  events unfolded this result became more inevitable.\n\nIn 1297 the Elector of Brandenburg, Duke of Saxony, and King of Czechia allied to enforce their interests. The Elector of Cologne, Gerard II, was associated with this group. In February 1298, the situation became alarming for King Adolf because Venceslas II and his brother-in-law Albert of Austria put aside their years of disputes and reached an agreement in the event that Adolf was deposed and Albert elected in his place.\n\nOn 1 May 1298, the Archbishop of Mainz invited the king Adolf to his court, so that the dispute could be decided there. Archbishop Gerard claimed he was authorised to do so as imperial arch-chancellor of Germany, according to an old legal principle. The meeting did not take place.\n\nA meeting between the Archbishop of Mainz, Albrecht of Saxony in Wittenberg, and three Margraves of Brandenburg on  23 June 1298 then led to a lawsuit against the king Adolf himself. The Archbishop of Cologne and the King of Czechia had previously authorised the Archbishop of Mainz to act in their names. The electoral princes relied on their right to vote, from which also they derived their right to oust a king.\n\nFollowing King Adolf\u2019s deposition came the election of [[Albert I of Habsburg]] as the new king. How this election took place is not very clear today, as the chroniclers have little to report. The question is open, for example, whether Albert actually initially did not want to accept the choice, as he would later assert against [[Pope Boniface VIII]].\n\nTo depose King Adolf was one thing; it was another to enforce the decision against him. King Adolf refused to accept this decision, but the conflict between him and the princely opposition was soon decided on the battlefield. On 2 July 1298 the armies of King Adolf and King Albert met at the [[Battle of G\u00f6llheim]]. After violent attacks, Adolf fell together with his standard-bearers and a few faithful. The slain Adolf\u2019s army turned to flee and quickly dispersed.\n\nAlbert of Austria was King from the election to his death.\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "The 1298 election really was the enthronement of Albert of Austria as outcome of the deposition of Adolf of Nassau. The electors probably did not plan from the beginning to depose the king, but as  events unfolded this result became more inevitable.\n\nIn 1297 the Elector of Brandenburg, Duke of Saxony, and King of Czechia allied to enforce their interests. The Elector of Cologne, Gerard II, was associated with this group. In February 1298, the situation became alarming for King Adolf because Venceslas II and his brother-in-law Albert of Austria put aside their years of disputes and reached an agreement in the event that Adolf was deposed and Albert elected in his place.\n\nOn 1 May 1298, the Archbishop of Mainz invited the king Adolf to his court, so that the dispute could be decided there. Archbishop Gerard claimed he was authorised to do so as imperial arch-chancellor of Germany, according to an old legal principle. The meeting did not take place.\n\nA meeting between the Archbishop of Mainz, Albrecht of Saxony in Wittenberg, and three Margraves of Brandenburg on  23 June 1298 then led to a lawsuit against the king Adolf himself. The Archbishop of Cologne and the King of Czechia had previously authorised the Archbishop of Mainz to act in their names. The electoral princes relied on their right to vote, from which also they derived their right to oust a king.\n\nFollowing King Adolf\u2019s deposition came the election of [[Albert I of Habsburg]] as the new king. How this election took place is not very clear today, as the chroniclers have little to report. The question is open, for example, whether Albert actually initially did not want to accept the choice, as he would later assert against [[Pope Boniface VIII]].\n\nTo depose King Adolf was one thing; it was another to enforce the decision against him. King Adolf refused to accept this decision, but the conflict between him and the princely opposition was soon decided on the battlefield. On 2 July 1298 the armies of King Adolf and King Albert met at the [[Battle of G\u00f6llheim]]. After violent attacks, Adolf fell together with his standard-bearers and a few faithful. The slain Adolf\u2019s army turned to flee and quickly dispersed.\n\nAlbert of Austria was King from the election to his death.\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added {{Uncategorized}} tag to article (UsingTwinkle)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1298_Imperial_election"}
{"title_page": "African-American art", "text_new": "{{African American topics sidebar|right}}'''African-American art''' is a broad term describing the visual arts of the [[United States|American]] [[Black people|black]] community ([[African American]]s). Influenced by various cultural traditions, including those of [[Africa]], [[Europe]] and the [[Americas]], traditional African-American art forms include the range of [[plastic arts]], from [[basket weaving]], [[pottery]], and [[quilting]] to [[woodcarving]] and [[painting]].\n\n== History ==\n\n===Pre-colonial, Antebellum and Civil War eras===\n[[File:John Bush powder horn carving.png|thumb|left|250px|Powder horn carved by John Bush, 1754.]]\n[[Image:PowersBibleQuilt 1898.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Harriet Powers]], ''Bible quilt'', Mixed Media. 1898.]]\nThe earliest evidence of African-American art in the [[United States]] is the work of skilled craftsmen slaves from [[New England]]. Two categories of slave craft items survive from colonial America: articles created for personal use by slaves and articles created for public use. Examples from the period between the 17th century and the early 19th century include:  small drums, quilts, wrought-iron figures, baskets, ceramic vessels, and gravestones.<ref>Sharon F. Patton, ''African-American Art'', Oxford University Press, 1998.</ref><ref name=\"African American Art book\">{{cite book |last1=Lewis |first1=Samella |title=African American Art and Artists |date=2003 |publisher=University of California Press}}</ref>\n\nMany of Africa's most skilled slave artisans were hired out by slave owners. With the consent of their masters, some slave artisans also were able to keep a small percentage of the wages earned in their free time and thereby save enough money to purchase their, and their families', freedom.<ref>Romare Bearden, Harry Henderson, ''A History of African-American Artists. From 1792 to the Present''. New York: [[Pantheon Books]], 1993.</ref>\n\nThe public works of art produced by slave craftsmen were an important contribution to the Colonial economy. In New England and the Mid-Atlantic colonies, slaves were apprenticed as goldsmiths, cabinetmakers, engravers, carvers portrait painters, carpenters, masons and iron workers. \nThe construction and decoration of the Janson House built on the Hudson River in 1712 was the work of African-Americans. Many of the oldest buildings in Louisiana, South Carolina and Georgia were built by craftsmen slaves.<ref name=\"African American Art book\" />\n\nIn the mid-eighteenth century, [[John Bush (provincial soldier)|John Bush]] was a powder horn carver and soldier with the Massachusetts militia fighting with the British in the [[French and Indian War]].<ref>USA Today Magazine. May 2005, Vol. 133 Issue 2720, pp. 48\u201352. 5p.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://journals.psu.edu/wph/article/viewFile/7624/7397|title=The Great Warpaths|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n[[Patrick H. Reason]], [[Joshua Johnson (painter)|Joshua Johnson]], and [[Scipio Moorhead]] were among the earliest known portrait artists, from the period of 1773\u20131887. Patronage by some white families allowed for private tutorship in special cases. Many of these sponsoring whites were [[Abolitionism in the United States|abolitionist]]s.  The artists received more encouragement and were better able to support themselves in cities, of which there were more in the North and border states.\n\n[[Harriet Powers]] (1837\u20131910) was an [[African-American]] folk artist and [[quilt]] maker from rural [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia, United States]], born into slavery. Now nationally recognized for her [[quilts]], she used traditional [[appliqu\u00e9]] techniques to record local legends, Bible stories, and astronomical events on her quilts.  Only two of her late quilts have survived: ''Bible Quilt 1886'' and ''Bible Quilt 1898''. Her quilts are considered among the finest examples of 19th-century Southern quilting,.<ref>Kyra E. Hicks (2009), ''This I Accomplish: Harriet Powers' Bible Quilt and Other Pieces''.</ref><ref>[http://www.earlywomenmasters.net/powers/index.html Harriet Powers] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071018043355/http://earlywomenmasters.net/powers/index.html |date=2007-10-18 }}, Early Women Masters</ref>\n\nLike Powers, the women of [[Gee's Bend]] developed a distinctive, bold, and sophisticated quilting style based on traditional American (and African-American) quilts, but with a geometric simplicity.  Although widely separated by geography, they have qualities reminiscent of [[Amish]] quilts and [[modern art]]. The [[The Quilts of Gees Bend|women of Gee's Bend]] passed their skills and aesthetic down through at least six generations to the present.<ref>''[https://web.archive.org/web/20040222230415/http://www.quiltsofgeesbend.com/history/ The Quilts of Gees Bend]''.</ref> At one time scholars believed slaves sometimes utilized [[quilt block]]s to alert other slaves about escape plans during the time of the [[Quilts of the Underground Railroad|Underground Railroad]],<ref>Raymond Dobard, Jr., Ph.D., and Jacqueline Tobin, ''Hidden in Plain View'', 1999.{{where|date=January 2011}}</ref> but most historians do not agree. [[African-American Quilts|Quilting]] remains alive as form of artistic expression in the African-American community.\n\n===Post-Civil War===\nAfter the Civil War, it became increasingly acceptable for African American-created works to be exhibited in museums, and artists increasingly produced works for this purpose. These were works mostly in the European romantic and classical traditions of landscapes and portraits. [[Edward Mitchell Bannister]], [[Henry Ossawa Tanner]] and [[Edmonia Lewis]] are the most notable of this time. Others include [[Grafton Tyler Brown]], [[Nelson Primus|Nelson A. Primus]] and [[Meta Vaux Warrick Fuller]].\n\nThe goal of widespread recognition across racial boundaries was first eased within America's big cities, including [[Philadelphia]], [[Boston]], [[Chicago]], [[New York City|New York]], and [[New Orleans]]. Even in these places, however, there were [[racial discrimination|discriminatory]] limitations. Abroad, however, African Americans were much better received. In Europe \u2014 especially [[Paris, France]] \u2014 these artists could express much more freedom in experimentation and education concerning techniques outside traditional western art. Freedom of expression was much more prevalent in Paris as well as [[Munich]] and [[Rome]] to a lesser extent.\n\n===The Harlem Renaissance to contemporary art===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:sanddunes by tanner.jpg|thumb|''Sand Dunes at Sunset, Atlantic City'' by Henry Ossawa Tanner is in the collection of the [[White House]], and hangs in the [[Green Room (White House)|Green Room]]. Acquired during the [[Bill Clinton|Clinton administration]] with funds from the [[White House Acquisition Trust]], it is the first artwork in the White House by an African American.]] -->{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe [[Harlem Renaissance]] was one of the most notable movements in African-American art. Certain freedoms and ideas that were already widespread in many parts of the world at the time had begun to spread into the artistic communities United States during the 1920s. During this period notable artists included [[Richmond Barth\u00e9]], [[Aaron Douglas]], [[Lawrence Harris]], [[Palmer Hayden]], William H. Johnson, [[Sargent Johnson]], [[John T. Biggers]], [[Earle Wilton Richardson]], [[Malvin Gray Johnson]], [[Archibald Motley]], [[Augusta Savage]], [[Hale Woodruff]], and photographer [[James Van Der Zee]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe establishment of the [[Harmon Foundation]] by art patron William E. Harmon in 1922 sponsored many artists through its [[William E. Harmon Foundation award for distinguished achievement among Negroes|Harmon Award]] and annual exhibitions. As it did with many such endeavors, the 1929 [[Great Depression]] largely ended funding for the arts for a time. While the Harmon Foundation still existed in this period, its financial support toward artists ended. The Harmon Foundation, however, continued supporting artists until 1967 by mounting exhibitions and offering funding for developing artists such as [[Jacob Lawrence]].<ref>Driskell, p. 121.</ref>\n\n[[Image:E.J.Martin.1990.jpg|thumb|upright|''Midnight Golfer'' by [[Eugene J. Martin]], mixed media collage on rag paper.]]\nThe [[United States Department of the Treasury|US Treasury Department]]'s [[Public Works of Art Project]] ineffectively attempted to provide support for artists in 1933. In 1935, President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] created the [[Works Progress Administration]] (WPA). The WPA provided for all American artists and proved especially helpful to African-American artists. Artists and writers both gained work that helped them survive the Depression. Among them were [[Jacob Lawrence]] and [[Richard Wright (author)|Richard Wright]]. Politics, human and social conditions all became the subjects of accepted art forms.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nImportant cities with significant black populations and important African-American art circles included Philadelphia, Boston, [[San Francisco]] and [[Washington, D.C.]] The WPA led to a new wave of important black art professors. Mixed media, abstract art, cubism, and social realism became not only acceptable, but desirable. Artists of the WPA united to form the 1935 [[Harlem Artists Guild]], which developed community art facilities in major cities.  Leading forms of art included drawing, sculpture, printmaking, painting, pottery, quilting, weaving and photography. By 1939, the costly WPA and its projects all were terminated.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn 1943, [[James Amos Porter|James A. Porter]], a professor in the Department of Art at [[Howard University]], wrote the first major text on African-American art and artists, ''Modern Negro Art''.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==== Mid-20th century ====\nIn the 1950s and 1960s, few African-American artists were widely known or accepted. Despite this, [[The Highwaymen (artists)|The Highwaymen]], a loose association of 26 [[African-American]] artists from [[Fort Pierce, Florida|Fort Pierce]], [[Florida]], created idyllic, quickly realized images of the Florida landscape and peddled some 200,000 of them from the trunks of their cars. In the 1950s and 1960s, it was impossible to find galleries interested in selling artworks by a group of unknown, self-taught African Americans,<ref>''[http://www.highwaymen.bigstep.com/generic4.html Painting Florida] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061108193514/http://www.highwaymen.bigstep.com/generic4.html |date=November 8, 2006 }}''</ref> so they sold their art directly to the public rather than through galleries and art agents. Rediscovered in the mid-1990s, today they are recognized as an important part of American folk history.<ref>''[http://www.go-star.com/framer/highwaymen.htm The Highwaymen] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071018072750/http://go-star.com/framer/highwaymen.htm |date=2007-10-18 }}'' By Ken Hall.</ref><ref>[http://www.gibson-highwaymen.com/generic81.html Updates & Snapshots 2006] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080311000000/http://www.gibson-highwaymen.com/generic81.html |date=March 11, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe current market price for an original Highwaymen painting can easily bring in thousands of dollars. In 2004 the original group of 26 Highwaymen were inducted into the Florida Artists Hall of Fame.<ref>''[http://www.floridahighwaymenpaintings.com The Florida Highwaymen]''</ref> Currently 8 of the 26 are deceased, including A. Hair, H. Newton, Ellis and George Buckner, A. Moran, L. Roberts, Hezekiah Baker and most recently Johnny Daniels. The full list of 26 can be found in the Florida Artists Hall of Fame, as well as various highwaymen and Florida art websites.\n[[Image:Jerry Harris.sculpture.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Jerry Harris]], ''Dogon mother and child'', constructed and carved wood with found objects, laminated clay (Bondo), and wooden dowels.]]\n\nAfter the [[Second World War]], some artists took a global approach, working and exhibiting abroad, in Paris, and as the decade wore on, relocated gradually in other welcoming cities such as Copenhagen, Amsterdam, and Stockholm: [[Barbara Chase-Riboud]], [[Edward Clark (artist)|Edward Clark]], [[Harvey Cropper]], [[Beauford Delaney]], [[Herbert Gentry]],<ref>Bearden. R., in ''An Ocean Apart: American Artists Abroad''. New York: Studio Museum in Harlem.</ref> [[Bill Hutson]], [[Clifford Jackson]],<ref>Malone, L., in ''An Ocean Apart: American Artists Abroad''. New York: Studio Museum in Harlem.</ref> [[Sam Middleton]],<ref>Williams, J. A., in ''An Ocean Apart: American Artists Abroad''. New York: Studio Museum in Harlem.</ref> Larry Potter, [[Haywood Bill Rivers]], [[Merton Simpson]], and [[Walter Williams (artist)|Walter Williams]].<ref>Driskell, David C., in ''An Ocean Apart: American Artists Abroad''. New York: Studio Museum in Harlem.</ref><ref>Mercer, Valerie (1996), ''Explorations in the City of Light''. New York: The Studio Museum in Harlem.</ref>\n\nSome African-American artists did make it into important New York galleries by the 1950s and 1960s: [[Horace Pippin]], [[Romare Bearden]], [[Jacob Lawrence]], [[William T. Williams]], [[Norman Lewis (artist)|Norman Lewis]], [[Thomas Sills]],<ref>I. C. K., (1957), \u201cThe Surprise of Painter Tom Sills,\u201d ''The Village Voice'', p. 17.</ref> and [[Sam Gilliam]] were among the few who had successfully been received in a gallery setting. The [[Civil Rights Movement]] of the 1960s and 1970s led artists to capture and express the times and changes. Galleries and community art centers developed for the purpose of displaying African-American art, and collegiate teaching positions were created by and for African-American artists. Some African-American women were also active in the [[Feminist art movement in the United States|feminist art movement]] in the 1970s. [[Faith Ringgold]] made work that featured black female subjects and that addressed the conjunction of racism and sexism in the U.S., while the collective [[Where We At (WWA)]] held exhibitions exclusively featuring the artwork of African-American women.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Brown|first=Kay|title=The Emergence of Black Women Artists: The Founding of 'Where We Ar'|journal=NKA Journal of Contemporary African Art|year=2011|volume=29|pages=118\u2013127}}</ref>\n\nBy the 1980s and 1990s, hip-hop graffiti became predominate in urban communities.  Most major cities had developed museums devoted to African-American artists. The [[National Endowment for the Arts]] provided increasing support for these artists.\n\n[[Kara Walker]], a contemporary American artist, is known for her exploration of race, gender, sexuality, violence and identity in her artworks.  Walker's [[silhouette]] images work to bridge unfinished folklore in the Antebellum South and are reminiscent of the earlier work of [[Harriet Powers]].  Her nightmarish yet fantastical images incorporate a cinematic feel. In 2007, Walker was listed among ''[[Time Magazine]]'''s \"100 Most Influential People in The World, Artists and Entertainers\".<ref>Kruger, Barbara (2007)[http://www.time.com/time/specials/2007/time100/article/0,28804,1595326_1595332_1616818,00.html \"Kara Walker\"], ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' online. Retrieved 26 July 2007.</ref>\n\nTextile artists are part of African-American art history. According to the 2010 Quilting in America industry survey, there are 1.6 million quilters in the United States.<ref>Kyra E. Hicks (2010), ''1.6 Million African American Quilters: Survey, Sites, and a Half-Dozen Art Quilt Blocks''.</ref>\n\nInfluential contemporary artists include [[Larry D. Alexander]], [[Laylah Ali]], [[Amalia Amaki]], [[Emma Amos (painter)|Emma Amos]], [[Jean-Michel Basquiat]], [[Dawoud Bey]], [[Camille Billops]], [[Mark Bradford]], [[Edward Clark (artist)|Edward Clark]], [[Willie Cole]], [[Robert Colescott]], [[Louis Delsarte]], [[David Driskell]], [[Leonardo Drew]], [[Mel Edwards]], [[Ricardo Francis]], [[Charles Gaines]], [[Ellen Gallagher]], [[Herbert Gentry]], [[Sam Gilliam]], [[David Hammons]], [[Jerry Harris]], Joseph Holston, [[Richard Hunt (sculptor)|Richard Hunt]], [[Martha Jackson-Jarvis]], [[Katie S. Mallory]], [[M. Scott Johnson]], [[Rashid Johnson]], [[Joe Lewis (artist)|Joe Lewis]], [[Glenn Ligon]], [[James Little (artist)|James Little]], [[Edward L. Loper, Sr.]], [[Alvin D. Loving]], [[Kerry James Marshall]], [[Eugene J. Martin]], [[Richard Mayhew]], [[Sam Middleton]], [[Howard McCalebb]], [[Charles McGill (artist)|Charles McGill]], [[Thaddeus Mosley]], Sana Musasama, Senga Nengudi, [[Joe Overstreet]], [[Martin Puryear]], [[Adrian Piper]], [[Howardena Pindell]], [[Faith Ringgold]], [[Gale Fulton Ross]], [[Alison Saar]], [[Betye Saar]], [[John Solomon Sandridge]], [[Raymond Saunders (artist)|Raymond Saunders]], [[John T. Scott]], [[Joyce Scott]], [[Gary Simmons (artist)|Gary Simmons]], [[Lorna Simpson]], [[Renee Stout]], [[Kara Walker]], [[Carrie Mae Weems]], [[Stanley Whitney]], [[William T. Williams]], [[Jack Whitten]], [[Fred Wilson (artist)|Fred Wilson]], [[Richard Wyatt, Jr.]], [[Richard Yarde]], and [[Purvis Young]], [[Kehinde Wiley]], [[Mickalene Thomas]], [[Barkley Hendricks]], [[Jeff Sonhouse]], [[William Aiken Walker|William Walker]], [[Ellsworth Ausby]], [[Che Baraka]], [[Emmett Wigglesworth]], [[Otto Neals]], [[Dindga McCannon]], [[Terry Dixon (artist)]], [[Frederick J. Brown]], and many others.\n\n[[Hip hop]] is a form of art for African Americans.<ref>https://www.jstor.org/stable/3042308?seq=1</ref>\n\nVery few African American artists included black [[nudity]] in their work.<ref>[https://books.google.de/books?id=tuc8DAAAQBAJ&pg=PA179&dq=african+americans+arts+nude+culture&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=african%20americans%20arts%20nude%20culture&f=false]</ref>\n\n==Collections of African-American art==\nMany American museums hold works by African American artists, including [[Smithsonian American Art Museum]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Smithsonian American Art Museum and Renwick Gallery |url=https://americanart.si.edu/ |website=americanart.si.edu |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>  Colleges and universities with important collections include [[Fisk University]], [[Spelman College]] and [[Howard University]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Museum of Fine Art {{!}} Spelman College |url=https://www.spelman.edu/about-us/museum-of-fine-art |website=www.spelman.edu |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> Other important collections of African-American art include the [[Walter O. Evans Collection of African American Art]], the [[Paul R. Jones]] collections at the [[University Museums at the University of Delaware#Mechanical Hall|University of Delaware]] and [[University of Alabama]], the [[David C. Driskell]] Art collection, the Harmon and Harriet Kelley Collection of African American Art, the [[Schomburg Center for Research in Black Culture]], and the Mott-Warsh collection.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States}}\n* [[African-American literature]]\n* [[African-American music]]\n* [[James A. Porter Colloquium on African American Art]]\n* [[African-American culture]]\n* [[List of African-American visual artists]]\n* [[The Highwaymen (artists)]]\n* [[Gullah/Geechee Cultural Heritage Corridor]]\n* [[Chicano art]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Sources ==\n*[[Romare Bearden]], Harry Henderson, ''A History of African-American Artists. From 1792 to the Present'', New York: Pantheon Books, 1993.\n*  Driskell, David C. (2001), ''The Other Side of Color: African American Art in the Collection of [[Camille Cosby|Camille O.]] and [[William H. Cosby, Jr.]]'' Pomegranate. {{ISBN|978-0-7649-1455-3}}\n*Sylvester, Melvin R. [https://web.archive.org/web/20070509035918/http://www.liunet.edu/cwis/cwp/library/aavaahp.htm ''African Americans in Visual Arts: A Historical Perspective'']. Long Island University. Retrieved January 23, 2005.\n*{{cite book |author= Perry, Regenia A. |url=http://libmma.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15324coll10/id/150414 |title=Selections of nineteenth-century Afro-American art| location=New York | publisher=The Metropolitan Museum of Art | year=1972}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons cat|African-American art}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080918074223/http://www.dos.state.fl.us/news/communications/pressRelease/pressRelease.cfm?id=48 Secretary of State Glenda E. Hood Announces 2004 Hall of Fame Inductees]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090921062535/http://www.highwaymenartist.com/about.html Promoting Natural Florida Through the Arts]\n*[http://blackartblog.blackartdepot.com Blog About African American Artists, Photographers, Galleries & Museums]\n*[[Jake Adam York]], [https://southernspaces.org/2012/medicine-memory-radcliffe-bailey-atlantas-high-museum-art \"Medicine as Memory: Radcliffe Bailey at Atlanta's High Museum of Art\"], ''Southern Spaces'', January 26, 2012.\n\n{{African American topics}}\n\n{{Feminist art movement in the United States}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:African American Art}}\n[[Category:African-American art| ]]\n[[Category:American contemporary art]]\n[[Category:African-American cultural history]]\n[[Category:African-American museums in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{African American topics sidebar|right}}'''African-American art''' is a broad term describing the visual arts of the [[United States|American]] [[Black people|black]] community ([[African American]]s). Influenced by various cultural traditions, including those of [[Africa]], [[Europe]] and the [[Americas]], traditional African-American art forms include the range of [[plastic arts]], from [[basket weaving]], [[pottery]], and [[quilting]] to [[woodcarving]] and [[painting]].\n\n== History ==\n\n===Pre-colonial, Antebellum and Civil War eras===\n[[File:John Bush powder horn carving.png|thumb|left|250px|Powder horn carved by John Bush, 1754.]]\n[[Image:PowersBibleQuilt 1898.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Harriet Powers]], ''Bible quilt'', Mixed Media. 1898.]]\nThe earliest evidence of African-American art in the [[United States]] is the work of skilled craftsmen slaves from [[New England]]. Two categories of slave craft items survive from colonial America: articles created for personal use by slaves and articles created for public use. Examples from the period between the 17th century and the early 19th century include:  small drums, quilts, wrought-iron figures, baskets, ceramic vessels, and gravestones.<ref>Sharon F. Patton, ''African-American Art'', Oxford University Press, 1998.</ref><ref name=\"African American Art book\">{{cite book |last1=Lewis |first1=Samella |title=African American Art and Artists |date=2003 |publisher=University of California Press}}</ref>\n\nMany of Africa's most skilled slave artisans were hired out by slave owners. With the consent of their masters, some slave artisans also were able to keep a small percentage of the wages earned in their free time and thereby save enough money to purchase their, and their families', freedom.<ref>Romare Bearden, Harry Henderson, ''A History of African-American Artists. From 1792 to the Present''. New York: [[Pantheon Books]], 1993.</ref>\n\nThe public works of art produced by slave craftsmen were an important contribution to the Colonial economy. In New England and the Mid-Atlantic colonies, slaves were apprenticed as goldsmiths, cabinetmakers, engravers, carvers portrait painters, carpenters, masons and iron workers. \nThe construction and decoration of the Janson House built on the Hudson River in 1712 was the work of African-Americans. Many of the oldest buildings in Louisiana, South Carolina and Georgia were built by craftsmen slaves.<ref name=\"African American Art book\" />\n\nIn the mid-eighteenth century, [[John Bush (provincial soldier)|John Bush]] was a powder horn carver and soldier with the Massachusetts militia fighting with the British in the [[French and Indian War]].<ref>USA Today Magazine. May 2005, Vol. 133 Issue 2720, pp. 48\u201352. 5p.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://journals.psu.edu/wph/article/viewFile/7624/7397|title=The Great Warpaths|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n[[Patrick H. Reason]], [[Joshua Johnson (painter)|Joshua Johnson]], and [[Scipio Moorhead]] were among the earliest known portrait artists, from the period of 1773\u20131887. Patronage by some white families allowed for private tutorship in special cases. Many of these sponsoring whites were [[Abolitionism in the United States|abolitionist]]s.  The artists received more encouragement and were better able to support themselves in cities, of which there were more in the North and border states.\n\n[[Harriet Powers]] (1837\u20131910) was an [[African-American]] folk artist and [[quilt]] maker from rural [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia, United States]], born into slavery. Now nationally recognized for her [[quilts]], she used traditional [[appliqu\u00e9]] techniques to record local legends, Bible stories, and astronomical events on her quilts.  Only two of her late quilts have survived: ''Bible Quilt 1886'' and ''Bible Quilt 1898''. Her quilts are considered among the finest examples of 19th-century Southern quilting,.<ref>Kyra E. Hicks (2009), ''This I Accomplish: Harriet Powers' Bible Quilt and Other Pieces''.</ref><ref>[http://www.earlywomenmasters.net/powers/index.html Harriet Powers] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071018043355/http://earlywomenmasters.net/powers/index.html |date=2007-10-18 }}, Early Women Masters</ref>\n\nLike Powers, the women of [[Gee's Bend]] developed a distinctive, bold, and sophisticated quilting style based on traditional American (and African-American) quilts, but with a geometric simplicity.  Although widely separated by geography, they have qualities reminiscent of [[Amish]] quilts and [[modern art]]. The [[The Quilts of Gees Bend|women of Gee's Bend]] passed their skills and aesthetic down through at least six generations to the present.<ref>''[https://web.archive.org/web/20040222230415/http://www.quiltsofgeesbend.com/history/ The Quilts of Gees Bend]''.</ref> At one time scholars believed slaves sometimes utilized [[quilt block]]s to alert other slaves about escape plans during the time of the [[Quilts of the Underground Railroad|Underground Railroad]],<ref>Raymond Dobard, Jr., Ph.D., and Jacqueline Tobin, ''Hidden in Plain View'', 1999.{{where|date=January 2011}}</ref> but most historians do not agree. [[African-American Quilts|Quilting]] remains alive as form of artistic expression in the African-American community.\n\n===Post-Civil War===\nAfter the Civil War, it became increasingly acceptable for African American-created works to be exhibited in museums, and artists increasingly produced works for this purpose. These were works mostly in the European romantic and classical traditions of landscapes and portraits. [[Edward Mitchell Bannister]], [[Henry Ossawa Tanner]] and [[Edmonia Lewis]] are the most notable of this time. Others include [[Grafton Tyler Brown]], [[Nelson Primus|Nelson A. Primus]] and [[Meta Vaux Warrick Fuller]].\n\nThe goal of widespread recognition across racial boundaries was first eased within America's big cities, including [[Philadelphia]], [[Boston]], [[Chicago]], [[New York City|New York]], and [[New Orleans]]. Even in these places, however, there were [[racial discrimination|discriminatory]] limitations. Abroad, however, African Americans were much better received. In Europe \u2014 especially [[Paris, France]] \u2014 these artists could express much more freedom in experimentation and education concerning techniques outside traditional western art. Freedom of expression was much more prevalent in Paris as well as [[Munich]] and [[Rome]] to a lesser extent.\n\n===The Harlem Renaissance to contemporary art===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:sanddunes by tanner.jpg|thumb|''Sand Dunes at Sunset, Atlantic City'' by Henry Ossawa Tanner is in the collection of the [[White House]], and hangs in the [[Green Room (White House)|Green Room]]. Acquired during the [[Bill Clinton|Clinton administration]] with funds from the [[White House Acquisition Trust]], it is the first artwork in the White House by an African American.]] -->{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe [[Harlem Renaissance]] was one of the most notable movements in African-American art. Certain freedoms and ideas that were already widespread in many parts of the world at the time had begun to spread into the artistic communities United States during the 1920s. During this period notable artists included [[Richmond Barth\u00e9]], [[Aaron Douglas]], [[Lawrence Harris]], [[Palmer Hayden]], William H. Johnson, [[Sargent Johnson]], [[John T. Biggers]], [[Earle Wilton Richardson]], [[Malvin Gray Johnson]], [[Archibald Motley]], [[Augusta Savage]], [[Hale Woodruff]], and photographer [[James Van Der Zee]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe establishment of the [[Harmon Foundation]] by art patron William E. Harmon in 1922 sponsored many artists through its [[William E. Harmon Foundation award for distinguished achievement among Negroes|Harmon Award]] and annual exhibitions. As it did with many such endeavors, the 1929 [[Great Depression]] largely ended funding for the arts for a time. While the Harmon Foundation still existed in this period, its financial support toward artists ended. The Harmon Foundation, however, continued supporting artists until 1967 by mounting exhibitions and offering funding for developing artists such as [[Jacob Lawrence]].<ref>Driskell, p. 121.</ref>\n\n[[Image:E.J.Martin.1990.jpg|thumb|upright|''Midnight Golfer'' by [[Eugene J. Martin]], mixed media collage on rag paper.]]\nThe [[United States Department of the Treasury|US Treasury Department]]'s [[Public Works of Art Project]] ineffectively attempted to provide support for artists in 1933. In 1935, President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] created the [[Works Progress Administration]] (WPA). The WPA provided for all American artists and proved especially helpful to African-American artists. Artists and writers both gained work that helped them survive the Depression. Among them were [[Jacob Lawrence]] and [[Richard Wright (author)|Richard Wright]]. Politics, human and social conditions all became the subjects of accepted art forms.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nImportant cities with significant black populations and important African-American art circles included Philadelphia, Boston, [[San Francisco]] and [[Washington, D.C.]] The WPA led to a new wave of important black art professors. Mixed media, abstract art, cubism, and social realism became not only acceptable, but desirable. Artists of the WPA united to form the 1935 [[Harlem Artists Guild]], which developed community art facilities in major cities.  Leading forms of art included drawing, sculpture, printmaking, painting, pottery, quilting, weaving and photography. By 1939, the costly WPA and its projects all were terminated.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn 1943, [[James Amos Porter|James A. Porter]], a professor in the Department of Art at [[Howard University]], wrote the first major text on African-American art and artists, ''Modern Negro Art''.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==== Mid-20th century ====\nIn the 1950s and 1960s, few African-American artists were widely known or accepted. Despite this, [[The Highwaymen (artists)|The Highwaymen]], a loose association of 26 [[African-American]] artists from [[Fort Pierce, Florida|Fort Pierce]], [[Florida]], created idyllic, quickly realized images of the Florida landscape and peddled some 200,000 of them from the trunks of their cars. In the 1950s and 1960s, it was impossible to find galleries interested in selling artworks by a group of unknown, self-taught African Americans,<ref>''[http://www.highwaymen.bigstep.com/generic4.html Painting Florida] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061108193514/http://www.highwaymen.bigstep.com/generic4.html |date=November 8, 2006 }}''</ref> so they sold their art directly to the public rather than through galleries and art agents. Rediscovered in the mid-1990s, today they are recognized as an important part of American folk history.<ref>''[http://www.go-star.com/framer/highwaymen.htm The Highwaymen] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071018072750/http://go-star.com/framer/highwaymen.htm |date=2007-10-18 }}'' By Ken Hall.</ref><ref>[http://www.gibson-highwaymen.com/generic81.html Updates & Snapshots 2006] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080311000000/http://www.gibson-highwaymen.com/generic81.html |date=March 11, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe current market price for an original Highwaymen painting can easily bring in thousands of dollars. In 2004 the original group of 26 Highwaymen were inducted into the Florida Artists Hall of Fame.<ref>''[http://www.floridahighwaymenpaintings.com The Florida Highwaymen]''</ref> Currently 8 of the 26 are deceased, including A. Hair, H. Newton, Ellis and George Buckner, A. Moran, L. Roberts, Hezekiah Baker and most recently Johnny Daniels. The full list of 26 can be found in the Florida Artists Hall of Fame, as well as various highwaymen and Florida art websites.\n[[Image:Jerry Harris.sculpture.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Jerry Harris]], ''Dogon mother and child'', constructed and carved wood with found objects, laminated clay (Bondo), and wooden dowels.]]\n\nAfter the [[Second World War]], some artists took a global approach, working and exhibiting abroad, in Paris, and as the decade wore on, relocated gradually in other welcoming cities such as Copenhagen, Amsterdam, and Stockholm: [[Barbara Chase-Riboud]], [[Edward Clark (artist)|Edward Clark]], [[Harvey Cropper]], [[Beauford Delaney]], [[Herbert Gentry]],<ref>Bearden. R., in ''An Ocean Apart: American Artists Abroad''. New York: Studio Museum in Harlem.</ref> [[Bill Hutson]], [[Clifford Jackson]],<ref>Malone, L., in ''An Ocean Apart: American Artists Abroad''. New York: Studio Museum in Harlem.</ref> [[Sam Middleton]],<ref>Williams, J. A., in ''An Ocean Apart: American Artists Abroad''. New York: Studio Museum in Harlem.</ref> Larry Potter, [[Haywood Bill Rivers]], [[Merton Simpson]], and [[Walter Williams (artist)|Walter Williams]].<ref>Driskell, David C., in ''An Ocean Apart: American Artists Abroad''. New York: Studio Museum in Harlem.</ref><ref>Mercer, Valerie (1996), ''Explorations in the City of Light''. New York: The Studio Museum in Harlem.</ref>\n\nSome African-American artists did make it into important New York galleries by the 1950s and 1960s: [[Horace Pippin]], [[Romare Bearden]], [[Jacob Lawrence]], [[William T. Williams]], [[Norman Lewis (artist)|Norman Lewis]], [[Thomas Sills]],<ref>I. C. K., (1957), \u201cThe Surprise of Painter Tom Sills,\u201d ''The Village Voice'', p. 17.</ref> and [[Sam Gilliam]] were among the few who had successfully been received in a gallery setting. The [[Civil Rights Movement]] of the 1960s and 1970s led artists to capture and express the times and changes. Galleries and community art centers developed for the purpose of displaying African-American art, and collegiate teaching positions were created by and for African-American artists. Some African-American women were also active in the [[Feminist art movement in the United States|feminist art movement]] in the 1970s. [[Faith Ringgold]] made work that featured black female subjects and that addressed the conjunction of racism and sexism in the U.S., while the collective [[Where We At (WWA)]] held exhibitions exclusively featuring the artwork of African-American women.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Brown|first=Kay|title=The Emergence of Black Women Artists: The Founding of 'Where We Ar'|journal=NKA Journal of Contemporary African Art|year=2011|volume=29|pages=118\u2013127}}</ref>\n\nBy the 1980s and 1990s, hip-hop graffiti became predominate in urban communities.  Most major cities had developed museums devoted to African-American artists. The [[National Endowment for the Arts]] provided increasing support for these artists.\n\n[[Kara Walker]], a contemporary American artist, is known for her exploration of race, gender, sexuality, violence and identity in her artworks.  Walker's [[silhouette]] images work to bridge unfinished folklore in the Antebellum South and are reminiscent of the earlier work of [[Harriet Powers]].  Her nightmarish yet fantastical images incorporate a cinematic feel. In 2007, Walker was listed among ''[[Time Magazine]]'''s \"100 Most Influential People in The World, Artists and Entertainers\".<ref>Kruger, Barbara (2007)[http://www.time.com/time/specials/2007/time100/article/0,28804,1595326_1595332_1616818,00.html \"Kara Walker\"], ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' online. Retrieved 26 July 2007.</ref>\n\nTextile artists are part of African-American art history. According to the 2010 Quilting in America industry survey, there are 1.6 million quilters in the United States.<ref>Kyra E. Hicks (2010), ''1.6 Million African American Quilters: Survey, Sites, and a Half-Dozen Art Quilt Blocks''.</ref>\n\nInfluential contemporary artists include [[Larry D. Alexander]], [[Laylah Ali]], [[Amalia Amaki]], [[Emma Amos (painter)|Emma Amos]], [[Jean-Michel Basquiat]], [[Dawoud Bey]], [[Camille Billops]], [[Mark Bradford]], [[Edward Clark (artist)|Edward Clark]], [[Willie Cole]], [[Robert Colescott]], [[Louis Delsarte]], [[David C. Driskell]], [[Leonardo Drew]], [[Mel Edwards]], [[Ricardo Francis]], [[Charles Gaines]], [[Ellen Gallagher]], [[Herbert Gentry]], [[Sam Gilliam]], [[David Hammons]], [[Jerry Harris]], Joseph Holston, [[Richard Hunt (sculptor)|Richard Hunt]], [[Martha Jackson-Jarvis]], [[Katie S. Mallory]], [[M. Scott Johnson]], [[Rashid Johnson]], [[Joe Lewis (artist)|Joe Lewis]], [[Glenn Ligon]], [[James Little (artist)|James Little]], [[Edward L. Loper, Sr.]], [[Alvin D. Loving]], [[Kerry James Marshall]], [[Eugene J. Martin]], [[Richard Mayhew]], [[Sam Middleton]], [[Howard McCalebb]], [[Charles McGill (artist)|Charles McGill]], [[Thaddeus Mosley]], Sana Musasama, Senga Nengudi, [[Joe Overstreet]], [[Martin Puryear]], [[Adrian Piper]], [[Howardena Pindell]], [[Faith Ringgold]], [[Gale Fulton Ross]], [[Alison Saar]], [[Betye Saar]], [[John Solomon Sandridge]], [[Raymond Saunders (artist)|Raymond Saunders]], [[John T. Scott]], [[Joyce Scott]], [[Gary Simmons (artist)|Gary Simmons]], [[Lorna Simpson]], [[Renee Stout]], [[Kara Walker]], [[Carrie Mae Weems]], [[Stanley Whitney]], [[William T. Williams]], [[Jack Whitten]], [[Fred Wilson (artist)|Fred Wilson]], [[Richard Wyatt, Jr.]], [[Richard Yarde]], and [[Purvis Young]], [[Kehinde Wiley]], [[Mickalene Thomas]], [[Barkley Hendricks]], [[Jeff Sonhouse]], [[William Aiken Walker|William Walker]], [[Ellsworth Ausby]], [[Che Baraka]], [[Emmett Wigglesworth]], [[Otto Neals]], [[Dindga McCannon]], [[Terry Dixon (artist)]], [[Frederick J. Brown]], and many others.\n\n[[Hip hop]] is a form of art for African Americans.<ref>https://www.jstor.org/stable/3042308?seq=1</ref>\n\nVery few African American artists included black [[nudity]] in their work.<ref>[https://books.google.de/books?id=tuc8DAAAQBAJ&pg=PA179&dq=african+americans+arts+nude+culture&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=african%20americans%20arts%20nude%20culture&f=false]</ref>\n\n==Collections of African-American art==\nMany American museums hold works by African American artists, including [[Smithsonian American Art Museum]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Smithsonian American Art Museum and Renwick Gallery |url=https://americanart.si.edu/ |website=americanart.si.edu |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>  Colleges and universities with important collections include [[Fisk University]], [[Spelman College]] and [[Howard University]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Museum of Fine Art {{!}} Spelman College |url=https://www.spelman.edu/about-us/museum-of-fine-art |website=www.spelman.edu |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> Other important collections of African-American art include the [[Walter O. Evans Collection of African American Art]], the [[Paul R. Jones]] collections at the [[University Museums at the University of Delaware#Mechanical Hall|University of Delaware]] and [[University of Alabama]], the [[David C. Driskell]] Art collection, the Harmon and Harriet Kelley Collection of African American Art, the [[Schomburg Center for Research in Black Culture]], and the Mott-Warsh collection.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States}}\n* [[African-American literature]]\n* [[African-American music]]\n* [[James A. Porter Colloquium on African American Art]]\n* [[African-American culture]]\n* [[List of African-American visual artists]]\n* [[The Highwaymen (artists)]]\n* [[Gullah/Geechee Cultural Heritage Corridor]]\n* [[Chicano art]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Sources ==\n*[[Romare Bearden]], Harry Henderson, ''A History of African-American Artists. From 1792 to the Present'', New York: Pantheon Books, 1993.\n*  Driskell, David C. (2001), ''The Other Side of Color: African American Art in the Collection of [[Camille Cosby|Camille O.]] and [[William H. Cosby, Jr.]]'' Pomegranate. {{ISBN|978-0-7649-1455-3}}\n*Sylvester, Melvin R. [https://web.archive.org/web/20070509035918/http://www.liunet.edu/cwis/cwp/library/aavaahp.htm ''African Americans in Visual Arts: A Historical Perspective'']. Long Island University. Retrieved January 23, 2005.\n*{{cite book |author= Perry, Regenia A. |url=http://libmma.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15324coll10/id/150414 |title=Selections of nineteenth-century Afro-American art| location=New York | publisher=The Metropolitan Museum of Art | year=1972}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons cat|African-American art}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080918074223/http://www.dos.state.fl.us/news/communications/pressRelease/pressRelease.cfm?id=48 Secretary of State Glenda E. Hood Announces 2004 Hall of Fame Inductees]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090921062535/http://www.highwaymenartist.com/about.html Promoting Natural Florida Through the Arts]\n*[http://blackartblog.blackartdepot.com Blog About African American Artists, Photographers, Galleries & Museums]\n*[[Jake Adam York]], [https://southernspaces.org/2012/medicine-memory-radcliffe-bailey-atlantas-high-museum-art \"Medicine as Memory: Radcliffe Bailey at Atlanta's High Museum of Art\"], ''Southern Spaces'', January 26, 2012.\n\n{{African American topics}}\n\n{{Feminist art movement in the United States}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:African American Art}}\n[[Category:African-American art| ]]\n[[Category:American contemporary art]]\n[[Category:African-American cultural history]]\n[[Category:African-American museums in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Scanlan", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/African-American_art"}
{"title_page": "Savitri Goonesekere", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=September 2011}}\n'''Savitri Goonesekere''' is a [[jurist]] and [[academic]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2003/09/21/fea23.html|title=Code of conduct to deal with sexual harassment in the work place|last=Liyanage|first=Jayanthi|date=21 September 2003|work=Sunday Observer|accessdate=23 September 2011}}</ref> from [[Sri Lanka]]. She is an international expert on the rights of children.\n\n==Career==\nGoonesekere was appointed as Professor of Law at the Open University of Sri Lanka in 1983. She worked as the Vice Chancellor of the [[University of Colombo]] from 1999 until 2002 and served on the editorial board of the [[United Nations Secretary General]]\u2019s Study on Violence Against Children.\n\nA prolific writer, Goonasekere was instrumental in the evolution of modern legal education in Sri Lanka. Her works on [[family law]] and [[child labour]] issues include: ''Child Labour in Sri Lanka: Learning from the Past'' (ILO:1993); ''Children, Law and Justice: A South Asian Perspective'' (Sage: 1998); and as editor, ''Violence, Law, and Women's Rights in South Asia'' (Sage:2004).\n\n==Other activities==\n* Global Partnership to End Violence Against Children, Member of the Board (since 2016)<ref>[http://www.end-violence.org/about-us/board Board] Global Partnership to End Violence Against Children.</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n* 2008 \u2013 [[Fukuoka Prize]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060211180611/http://www.adb.org/gender/forum/members.asp Asian Development bank]\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goonesekere, Savitri}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan jurists]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese writers]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese academics]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Colombo]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Colombo]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan women academics]]\n\n\n{{SriLanka-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=September 2011}}\n'''Savitri Goonesekere''' is a [[jurist]] and [[academic]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2003/09/21/fea23.html|title=Code of conduct to deal with sexual harassment in the work place|last=Liyanage|first=Jayanthi|date=21 September 2003|work=Sunday Observer|accessdate=23 September 2011}}</ref> from [[Sri Lanka]]. She is an international expert on the rights of children. \n\n==Career==\nGoonesekere was appointed as Professor of Law at the Open University of Sri Lanka in 1983. She worked as the Vice Chancellor of the [[University of Colombo]] from 1999 until 2002 and served on the editorial board of the [[United Nations Secretary General]]\u2019s Study on Violence Against Children.\n\nA prolific writer, Goonasekere was instrumental in the evolution of modern legal education in Sri Lanka. Her works on [[family law]] and [[child labour]] issues include: ''Child Labour in Sri Lanka: Learning from the Past'' (ILO:1993); ''Children, Law and Justice: A South Asian Perspective'' (Sage: 1998); and as editor, ''Violence, Law, and Women's Rights in South Asia'' (Sage:2004). \n\n==Other activities==\n* Global Partnership to End Violence Against Children, Member of the Board (since 2016)<ref>[http://www.end-violence.org/about-us/board Board] Global Partnership to End Violence Against Children.</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n* 2008 \u2013 [[Fukuoka Prize]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060211180611/http://www.adb.org/gender/forum/members.asp Asian Development bank]\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goonesekere, Savitri}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan jurists]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese writers]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese academics]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Colombo]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Colombo]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan women academics]]\n\n\n{{SriLanka-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Savitri_Goonesekere"}
{"title_page": "Sign of the horns", "text_new": "{{redirects|Corna}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{refimprove|date=June 2013}}\n{{inline|date=May 2017}}\n\n{{Primary sources|date=August 2008}}\n}}\n\n[[File:Mano cornuta by-RaBoe001.jpg|thumb|upright|A demonstration of the sign of the horns.]]\n\nThe '''sign of the horns''' is a [[hand]] [[gesture]] with a variety of meanings and uses in various cultures.  It is formed by extending the [[index finger|index]] and [[little finger]]s while holding the [[middle finger|middle]] and [[ring finger]]s down with the [[thumb]].\n\n==Spiritual and superstitious meaning==\n\nIn [[Hinduism]], the hand gesture is known as the \"[[List of mudras (yoga)#Hasta (hand mudras)|Apana yogic mudra]]\".<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/rajinikanth-politics-party-symbol-apana-mudra-detoxification-purification-5007863/|title=Is Rajinikanth\u2019s party symbol the same as Apana Mudra for \u2018detoxification and purification\u2019?|date=January 4, 2018}}</ref> In [[Indian classical dance]] forms the hand gesture symbolises the [[Asiatic lion#In mythology, religion, culture and art|Lion]]<ref name=\"auto\"/>. In [[Buddhism]] it is seen as an [[Apotropaic magic|apotropaic]] gesture very commonly used by [[Gautama Buddha]] as \"Karana Mudra\" which is synonymous with [[Exorcism#Buddhism|expulsion of demons]] and removal of obstacles like sickness or negative thoughts.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nThe [[apotropaic]] usage of the sign can also be seen in [[Italy]] and in other [[Mediterranean]] cultures where, when confronted with unfortunate events, or simply when these events are mentioned, the sign of the horns may be given to ward off bad luck. It is also used traditionally to counter or ward off the \"[[evil eye]]\" (''malocchio'' in Italian). In Italy specifically, the gesture is known as the ''corna''. With fingers pointing down, it is a common Mediterranean apotropaic gesture, by which people seek protection in unlucky situations (it is thus a more Mediterranean equivalent of [[knocking on wood]]). Thus, for example, the [[President of the Italian Republic]], [[Giovanni Leone]], shocked the country when, while in [[Naples]] during an [[outbreak]] of [[cholera]], he shook the hands of [[patient]]s with one hand while with the other behind his back he superstitiously made the ''corna'', presumably to ward off the disease or in reaction to being confronted by such misfortune. This act was well documented by the [[journalist]]s and [[photographer]]s who were right behind him, a fact that had escaped President Leone's mind in that moment.{{cn|date=January 2020}} \n\nIn Italy and other parts of the [[Mediterranean region]], the gesture must usually be performed with the fingers tilting downward to signify the warding off of bad luck; in the same region and elsewhere, the gesture may take a different, offensive and insulting meaning if it is performed with fingers upward or if directed aggressively towards someone in a swiveling motion (see section below). In Italy, one can also \"touch iron\" (''tocca ferro'') or touch one's nose to ward off bad luck. Males in Italy may also grab their [[testicle]]s when confronted by bad luck; however, this is considered more vulgar.\n\nIn [[Peru]] one says ''contra'' (against). In the [[Dominican Republic]] the expression is ''zafa'', said against curses known as ''fuk\u00fa''. All of these gestures are meant to conjure supernatural protection.\n\nThe sign of the horns is used during religious rituals in Wicca, to invoke or represent the [[Horned god]].<ref>''Wicca: A Guide for the Solitary Practitioner'' by Scott Cunningham, p. 42.</ref>\n\n==Offensive gesture==\nIn many [[Mediterranean basin|Mediterranean]] and Latin countries, such as [[Brazil]], [[Colombia]], [[Greece]], [[Italy]], [[Portugal]], [[Spain]], [[Mexico]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/galleries/Rude-hand-gestures-of-the-world/|title=Rude hand gestures of the world (don't try these on holiday)|date=February 4, 2016|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theloop.ca/living/funwind/photo-gallery/-/p/6407/-International-field-guide-to-rude-hand-gestures/2442503 |title=International field guide to rude hand gestures |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214213945/http://www.theloop.ca/living/funwind/photo-gallery/-/p/6407/-International-field-guide-to-rude-hand-gestures/2442503 |archivedate=2013-12-14 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.buzzle.com/articles/hand-gestures-in-different-cultures.html|title=Hand Gestures in Different Cultures}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rHS39OG4GG4C |title=Rude Hand Gestures of the World: A Guide to Offending without Words By Romana Lefevre |isbn=9781452110172 |author1=Lefevre |first1=Romana |date=2011-10-21 }}</ref> when directed towards someone and swiveled back and forth, the sign implies [[cuckold]]ry; the common words for ''cuckolded'' in Italian, Greek and Spanish are {{lang|it|cornuto}}, {{lang|el|\u03ba\u03b5\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03ac\u03c2}} ({{lang|el-Latn|keratas}}) and {{lang|es|cornudo}}, respectively, literally meaning \"horned\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.reading-body-language.co.uk/gestures2.html |title=Hand Gestures Part Two \u2014 The Cuckold Gesture |publisher=Reading-Body-Language.co.uk}}</ref> During a [[European Union]] meeting in February 2002, then-current Italian prime minister [[Silvio Berlusconi]] was photographed performing this gesture behind the back of [[Josep Piqu\u00e9]], the Spanish foreign minister.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1874098_1874099_1874139,00.html|title=Top 10 Worst Silvio Berlusconi Gaffes|date=8 December 2012|publisher=|accessdate=21 May 2017|via=content.time.com}}</ref>\n\n==Northwestern European and North American popular culture==\n\n===Contemporary use by musicians and fans===\nThe 1969 back album cover for ''[[Witchcraft Destroys Minds & Reaps Souls]]'' on Mercury Records by Chicago-based psychedelic-occult rock band [[Coven (band)|Coven]], led by singer [[Jinx Dawson]], pictured Coven band members giving the \"sign of the horns\". Starting in early 1968, Coven concerts always began and ended with Dawson giving the sign on stage.{{fact|date=December 2017}}\n\nOn the cover of [[the Beatles]]' ''[[Yellow Submarine (album)|Yellow Submarine]]'' album (1969), the cartoon of [[John Lennon]]'s right hand is making the sign above [[Paul McCartney]]'s head. Some fans interpreted this as one of the many supposed \"[[Paul is dead]]\" clues. Some may think it is possible that the cartoonist misrepresented the [[ILY sign|sign for \"I love you\"]], which is very similar and more in keeping with the band's public message and image. However, the 1969 cartoon is based on many photos of John Lennon making the hand sign in 1967. One of these photos of Lennon doing the hand sign appears on the cover of a Beatles single release shortly after, making it the first time the hand sign appears on a rock release.\n\nThe sign is also used in various Disney movies. It can be seen in the medieval-style opening sequence of the 1971 British-American Disney movie ''[[Bedknobs and Broomsticks]]'' as a goat-legged figure with a jester's cap leading a procession of outlandish looking figures, flashes the sign.\n\nBeginning in the early 1970s, the horns were known as the \"P-Funk sign\" to fans of [[Parliament-Funkadelic]]. It was used by [[George Clinton (musician)|George Clinton]] and [[Bootsy Collins]] as the password to the Mothership,<ref name=appleford>{{cite web |url=http://www.lacitybeat.com/article.php?id=1216&IssueNum=66 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071122030548/http://www.lacitybeat.com/article.php?id=1216&IssueNum=66 |archivedate=November 22, 2007 |title=Odyssey of the Devil Horns |first=Steve |last=Appleford |publisher=Los Angeles City Beat |date=September 9, 2004 |quote=A friend arranges a meeting with Clinton. I hand him a photograph of Dio making the hand signal, and tell him this is the man (or one of them) credited with bringing it to rock. Clinton stares at the picture for a long, silent minute, breathing heavily. Another minute passes. He's never heard of Ronnie James Dio. It's the P-Funk sign, man.}}</ref> a central element in Parliament's science-fiction [[P-Funk mythology|mythology]], and fans used it in return to show their enthusiasm for the band. Collins is depicted showing the P-Funk sign on the cover of his 1977 album ''[[Ahh... The Name Is Bootsy, Baby!]]''  \n\n[[Frank Zappa]] can be seen jokingly making the gesture in the 1979 film ''[[Baby Snakes]]'' in response to the audience, commenting, \"That's right, spindle twice.\"\n\nIn 1977, a painting<!-- animated painting??? --> of [[Gene Simmons]] (of the band [[Kiss (band)|KISS]]) exhibits the sign on the cover of ''[[Love Gun]]'', the band's sixth studio album. Simmons still utilizes the sign, both on and off stage.\n\n[[Marlon Brando]] makes the sign whilst singing \"[[Luck Be a Lady]]\" in the 1955 film ''[[Guys and Dolls (film)|Guys and Dolls]]'', seeming to indicate it was a sign for snake eyes in the craps game he is playing for the gamblers' souls.<ref>{{cite web|title=Marlon Brando-Luck Be a Lady|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=f-JzdRJCcsg|website=youtube.com|accessdate=13 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1985 film, ''The Breakfast Club'', Richard \"Dick\" Vernon is the grumpy vice principal of Shermer High School and the main antagonist of the film. One of his most famous lines is, \" Don't mess with the bull young man, you'll get the horns\", flashing the sign of the horns while rotating his wrist.\n\nIn one episode of the popular animated series [[The Simpsons]], a female tramp is seen warding off a male tramp using the sign of the horns using her thumbs and index fingers, screaming 'And you're a three-headed devil dog! Devil dog!'\n\nFor the 2016 Indian movie ''[[Rock On 2]]'', The \"2\" in the title is stylized with the sign of the horns, with the two extended fingers representing \"2\".\n\n===Heavy metal culture===\n[[File:Dio throwing Horns.jpg|thumb|Vocalist [[Ronnie James Dio]] making the sign at a [[Heaven & Hell (band)|Heaven and Hell]] concert in 2007. The gesture is quite common within [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] culture.]]\n\n[[Ronnie James Dio]] was known for popularizing the sign of the horns in [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]].<ref name=\"appleford\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/columns/junkyard/the_devils_horns_a_rock_and_roll_symbol.html |title=The Devil's Horns: A Rock And Roll Symbol |publisher=Ultimate-Guitar.com |date=September 7, 2005}}</ref> He claimed his Italian grandmother used it to ward off the [[evil eye]] (which is known in Southern Italy as ''[[Evil eye|malocchio]]''). Dio began using the sign soon after joining the metal band [[Black Sabbath]] in 1979. The previous singer in the band, [[Ozzy Osbourne]], was rather well known for using the [[V Sign|\"peace\"]] sign at concerts, raising the index and middle finger in the form of a V. Dio, in an attempt to connect with the fans, wanted to similarly use a hand gesture. However, not wanting to copy Osbourne, he chose to use the sign his grandmother always made.<ref>Ronnie James Dio interview in the 2005 documentary ''[[Metal: A Headbanger's Journey]]''. In the interview he also ridicules Gene Simmons for taking credit for originating use of the sign in heavy metal, attributing the claim to Simmons' well-known egotism.</ref> The horns became famous in metal concerts very soon after Black Sabbath's first tour with Dio. The sign would later be appropriated by heavy metal fans under the name \"maloik\", a corruption of the original ''malocchio''.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\n[[Geezer Butler|Terry \"Geezer\" Butler]] of Black Sabbath can be seen \"raising the horns\" in a photograph taken in 1971. The photograph is included in the CD booklet of the ''[[Symptom of the Universe: The Original Black Sabbath 1970\u20131978]]'' compilation album. This would indicate that there had been some association between the \"horns\" and heavy metal before Dio's popularization of it.\n\nWhen asked if he was the one who introduced the hand gesture to metal subculture, Dio said in a 2001 interview with Metal-Rules.com:\n\n{{quote|I doubt very much if I would be the first one who ever did that. That's like saying I invented the wheel, I'm sure someone did that at some other point. I think you'd have to say that I made it fashionable. I used it so much and all the time and it had become my trademark until the [[Britney Spears]] audience decided to do it as well. So it kind of lost its meaning with that. But it was \u2026 I was in Sabbath at the time. It was a symbol that I thought was reflective of what that band was supposed to be all about. It's NOT the devil's sign like we're here with the devil. It's an Italian thing I got from my Grandmother called the \"Malocchio\". It's to ward off the Evil Eye or to give the Evil Eye, depending on which way you do it. It's just a symbol but it had magical incantations and attitudes to it and I felt it worked very well with Sabbath. So I became very noted for it and then everybody else started to pick up on it and away it went. But I would never say I take credit for being the first to do it. I say because I did it so much that it became the symbol of rock and roll of some kind.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metal-rules.com/zine/index.php?option=content&task=view&id=666 |title=Dio - Interviewed By EvilG |publisher=Metal-Rules.com |date=March 9, 2001}}</ref>}}\n\n[[Gene Simmons]] of the rock group [[Kiss (band)|KISS]] attempted to claim the \"devil horns\" hand gesture for his own. According to CBS News, \"Simmons filed an application on Friday, June 16, 2017 with the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office for a trademark on the hand gesture he regularly uses during concerts and public appearances \u2014 thumb, index and pinky fingers extended, with the middle and ring fingers folded down. According to Simmons, this hand gesture was first used in commerce\u00a0\u2014\u00a0by him\u00a0\u2014\u00a0on Nov. 14, 1974. He is claiming the hand gesture should be trademarked for \"entertainment, namely live performances by a musical artist [and] personal appearances by a musical artist.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/gene-simmons-trademark-devil-horns-hand-gesture/|title=Gene Simmons wants to trademark \u201cdevil horns\u201d hand gesture|publisher=CBS News|date=June 15, 2017}}</ref> Simmons abandoned this application on June 21, 2017.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/legalentertainment/2017/06/21/breaking-gene-simmons-abandons-hand-gesture-trademark-application/#77f2bc74faac|title=Gene Simmons Abandons Hand Gesture Trademark Application |magazine=Forbes |date=June 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Electronic communication===\nIn text-based electronic communication, the sign of the horns is represented with the <code>\\../</code>, <code>\\m/</code> or <code>|m|</code> emoticon and sometimes with <code>/../</code>. The [[Unicode]] character U+1F918 \ud83e\udd18 SIGN OF THE HORNS was introduced in Unicode 8.0 as an [[emoji]], on June 17, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2015/06/burrito-sign-of-the-horns-and-35-other-emoji-approved-in-unicode-8-0/|title=\u201cBurrito,\u201d \u201cSign Of The Horns,\u201d and 35 other emoji approved in Unicode 8.0|publisher=|accessdate=21 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Gang hand signal===\nThe \"sign of the horns\" hand gesture is used in [[criminal gang]] subcultures to indicate membership or affiliation with [[MS-13|Mara Salvatrucha]]. The significance is both the resemblance of an inverted \"devil horns\" to the Latin letter 'M', and in the broader demonic connotation, of fierceness and nonconformity.  \n[[File:Mara_Salvatrucha_MS13.jpg|thumbnail|An [[MS-13]] gang member displays \"sign of the horns\" gang sign]]\n\n===Sports culture===\n[[File:hookemhorns.jpg|thumbnail|A fan displays the Hook 'em Horns during a Texas football game versus Arkansas.]]\n\n[[Hook 'em Horns]] is the slogan and hand signal of the [[University of Texas at Austin]]. Students and alumni of the university employ a greeting consisting of the phrase \"Hook 'em\" or \"Hook 'em Horns\" and also use the phrase as a parting good-bye or as the closing line in a letter or story.  The [[gesture]] is meant to approximate the shape of the head and horns of the [[University of Texas at Austin|UT]] mascot, the [[Texas longhorn (cattle)|Texas Longhorn]] [[Bevo (mascot)|Bevo]].\n\nFans of the [[University of South Florida]] Bulls use the same hand sign at their athletic events, except that the hand is turned around and facing the other way.  With the middle and ring finger extending towards the person presenting the \"Go Bulls\" sign.\n\nFans of [[North Dakota State University]] Bison athletics also use a similar hand gesture, known as \"Go Bison!\"  The pinky and index fingers are usually slightly bent, however, to mimic the shape of a [[bison]]'s horns.\n\nFans of [[North Carolina State University]] Wolfpack athletics use a similar gesture with the middle and ring fingers moving up and down over the thumb to mimic a wolf's jaw.\n\nFans of  [[University of California, Irvine]] Anteaters use a similar sign with the middle and ring fingers out to resemble the head of the mighty anteater.\n\nFans of [[University of Nevada, Reno]] Wolf Pack athletics use a similar sign with the middle and ring fingers out to resemble the wolf's snout. \n\nA variation of this hand gesture is also used in the [[professional wrestling]] industry, which fans dub the \"Too Sweet\". It was possibly innovated by [[Scott Hall]] and the other members of [[The Kliq]], and has since been attributed to other wrestling groups such as [[New World Order (professional wrestling)|the nWo]] and [[Bullet Club]], as well as individual wrestlers such as [[Finn B\u00e1lor]].\n\nFans of [[University of Utah]] athletics, particularly football and gymnastics, use a gesture where the index and pinky finger are straight and parallel to each other, forming a block \"U.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alumni.utah.edu/muss/membership/ |title=MUSS - Student Cheer Section for the U of U Utes - University of Utah Alumni Association &#124; MUSS |publisher=Alumni.utah.edu |date=2011-03-18 |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref>\n\nFans of [[Northwestern State University]] Demon athletics also use a similar hand gesture, known as \"Fork 'em!\"  The pinky and index fingers are extended but a little more parallel to each other resembling the horns on a demon.\n\n[[Arizona State University]] [[Sun Devil]] fans make a pitchfork sign by extending the index and middle fingers, as well as the pinky. The thumb holds down the ring finger to complete the gesture.\n\nFans of the [[Wichita State University]] Shockers frequently hold up their middle finger in addition to the pointer and pinky fingers as a reference to the [[Shocker (hand gesture)|comic sexual act]].\n\nFans of the [[Grand Canyon University]] Antelopes use this hand gesture with a slight variation by touching the tips of the ring and middle finger with the thumb to form the shape of an antelope and its horns. Often followed by the phrase \"Lopes up\".\n\nFans of the [[Universidad de Chile]] soccer team use this gesture to represent their support for the team by forming a U-shaped hand gesture, often followed by the phrase \"Grande la U\".\n\n== See also ==\n* [[ILY sign]] is sometimes confused with this gesture because many users tend to do the \"horns\" improperly by extending their thumb.\n* [[Shaka sign]]\n* [[Cornicello]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Sign of the horns}}\n*[http://www.rockandrollconfidential.com/archives/archives_death.php Rock and Roll Confidential on their logo]\n*{{cite magazine |url=http://www.chartattack.com/news/31464/ronnie-james-dio-re-claims-the-devil-horns |first=Neil |last=Haverty |date=2002-05-30 |title=Ronnie James Dio Re-Claims the Devil Horns |magazine=[[Chart (magazine)|Chart]] |accessdate=2009-09-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091003114135/http://www.chartattack.com/news/31464/ronnie-james-dio-re-claims-the-devil-horns |archivedate=2009-10-03 }}\n*[https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2005/01/images/20050120-1_p44294-227-515h.html President George W. Bush, gestures the \"Hook 'em, horns,\" the salute of the University of Texas Longhorns.(...)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071122030548/http://www.lacitybeat.com/article.php?id=1216&IssueNum=66 Odyssey of the Devil Horns: Who is responsible for bringing metal's famous hand signal to the tribe?] ''[[Los Angeles CityBeat]]'', Sept. 9, 2004\n\n{{Gestures}}\n{{Superstitions}}\n{{Rock festival}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sign Of The Horns}}\n[[Category:Hand gestures]]\n[[Category:Heavy metal subculture]]\n[[Category:Superstitions of Italy]]\n[[Category:Symbols]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirects|Corna}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{refimprove|date=June 2013}}\n{{inline|date=May 2017}}\n\n{{Primary sources|date=August 2008}}\n}}\n\n[[File:Mano cornuta by-RaBoe001.jpg|thumb|upright|A demonstration of the sign of the horns.]]\n\nThe '''sign of the horns''' is a [[hand]] [[gesture]] with a variety of meanings and uses in various cultures.  It is formed by extending the [[index finger|index]] and [[little finger]]s while holding the [[middle finger|middle]] and [[ring finger]]s down with the [[thumb]].\n\n==Spiritual and superstitious meaning==\n\nIn [[Hinduism]], the hand gesture is known as the \"[[List of mudras (yoga)#Hasta (hand mudras)|Apana yogic mudra]]\".<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/rajinikanth-politics-party-symbol-apana-mudra-detoxification-purification-5007863/|title=Is Rajinikanth\u2019s party symbol the same as Apana Mudra for \u2018detoxification and purification\u2019?|date=January 4, 2018}}</ref> In [[Indian classical dance]] forms the hand gesture symbolises the [[Asiatic lion#In mythology, religion, culture and art|Lion]]<ref name=\"auto\"/>. In [[Buddhism]] it is seen as an [[Apotropaic magic|apotropaic]] gesture very commonly used by [[Gautama Buddha]] as \"Karana Mudra\" which is synonymous with [[Exorcism#Buddhism|expulsion of demons]] and removal of obstacles like sickness or negative thoughts.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nThe [[apotropaic]] usage of the sign can also be seen in [[Italy]] and in other [[Mediterranean]] cultures where, when confronted with unfortunate events, or simply when these events are mentioned, the sign of the horns may be given to ward off bad luck. It is also used traditionally to counter or ward off the \"[[evil eye]]\" (''malocchio'' in Italian). In Italy specifically, the gesture is known as the ''corna''. With fingers pointing down, it is a common Mediterranean apotropaic gesture, by which people seek protection in unlucky situations (it is thus a more Mediterranean equivalent of [[knocking on wood]]). Thus, for example, the [[President of the Italian Republic]], [[Giovanni Leone]], shocked the country when, while in [[Naples]] during an [[outbreak]] of [[cholera]], he shook the hands of [[patient]]s with one hand while with the other behind his back he superstitiously made the ''corna'', presumably to ward off the disease or in reaction to being confronted by such misfortune. This act was well documented by the [[journalist]]s and [[photographer]]s who were right behind him, a fact that had escaped President Leone's mind in that moment.{{cn|date=January 2020}} \n\nIn Italy and other parts of the [[Mediterranean region]], the gesture must usually be performed with the fingers tilting downward to signify the warding off of bad luck; in the same region and elsewhere, the gesture may take a different, offensive and insulting meaning if it is performed with fingers upward or if directed aggressively towards someone in a swiveling motion (see section below). In Italy, one can also \"touch iron\" (''tocca ferro'') or touch one's nose to ward off bad luck. Males in Italy may also grab their [[testicle]]s when confronted by bad luck; however, this is considered more vulgar.\n\nIn [[Peru]] one says ''contra'' (against). In the [[Dominican Republic]] the expression is ''zafa'', said against curses known as ''fuk\u00fa''. All of these gestures are meant to conjure supernatural protection.\n\nThe sign of the horns is used during religious rituals in Wicca, to invoke or represent the [[Horned god]].<ref>''Wicca: A Guide for the Solitary Practitioner'' by Scott Cunningham, p. 42.</ref>\n\n==Offensive gesture==\nIn many [[Mediterranean basin|Mediterranean]] and Latin countries, such as [[Brazil]], [[Colombia]], [[Greece]], [[Italy]], [[Portugal]], [[Spain]], [[Mexico]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/galleries/Rude-hand-gestures-of-the-world/|title=Rude hand gestures of the world (don't try these on holiday)|date=February 4, 2016|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theloop.ca/living/funwind/photo-gallery/-/p/6407/-International-field-guide-to-rude-hand-gestures/2442503 |title=International field guide to rude hand gestures |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214213945/http://www.theloop.ca/living/funwind/photo-gallery/-/p/6407/-International-field-guide-to-rude-hand-gestures/2442503 |archivedate=2013-12-14 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.buzzle.com/articles/hand-gestures-in-different-cultures.html|title=Hand Gestures in Different Cultures}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rHS39OG4GG4C |title=Rude Hand Gestures of the World: A Guide to Offending without Words By Romana Lefevre |isbn=9781452110172 |author1=Lefevre |first1=Romana |date=2011-10-21 }}</ref> when directed towards someone and swiveled back and forth, the sign implies [[cuckold]]ry; the common words for ''cuckolded'' in Italian, Greek and Spanish are {{lang|it|cornuto}}, {{lang|el|\u03ba\u03b5\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03ac\u03c2}} ({{lang|el-Latn|keratas}}) and {{lang|es|cornudo}}, respectively, literally meaning \"horned\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.reading-body-language.co.uk/gestures2.html |title=Hand Gestures Part Two \u2014 The Cuckold Gesture |publisher=Reading-Body-Language.co.uk}}</ref> During a [[European Union]] meeting in February 2002, then-current Italian prime minister [[Silvio Berlusconi]] was photographed performing this gesture behind the back of [[Josep Piqu\u00e9]], the Spanish foreign minister.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1874098_1874099_1874139,00.html|title=Top 10 Worst Silvio Berlusconi Gaffes|date=8 December 2012|publisher=|accessdate=21 May 2017|via=content.time.com}}</ref>\n\n==Northwestern European and North American popular culture==\n\n===Contemporary use by musicians and fans===\nThe 1969 back album cover for ''[[Witchcraft Destroys Minds & Reaps Souls]]'' on Mercury Records by Chicago-based psychedelic-occult rock band [[Coven (band)|Coven]], led by singer [[Jinx Dawson]], pictured Coven band members giving the \"sign of the horns\". Starting in early 1968, Coven concerts always began and ended with Dawson giving the sign on stage.{{fact|date=December 2017}}\n\nOn the cover of [[the Beatles]]' ''[[Yellow Submarine (album)|Yellow Submarine]]'' album (1969), the cartoon of [[John Lennon]]'s right hand is making the sign above [[Paul McCartney]]'s head. Some fans interpreted this as one of the many supposed \"[[Paul is dead]]\" clues. Some may think it is possible that the cartoonist misrepresented the [[ILY sign|sign for \"I love you\"]], which is very similar and more in keeping with the band's public message and image. However, the 1969 cartoon is based on many photos of John Lennon making the hand sign in 1967. One of these photos of Lennon doing the hand sign appears on the cover of a Beatles single release shortly after, making it the first time the hand sign appears on a rock release.\n\nThe sign is also used in various Disney movies. It can be seen in the medieval-style opening sequence of the 1971 British-American Disney movie ''[[Bedknobs and Broomsticks]]'' as a goat-legged figure with a jester's cap leading a procession of outlandish looking figures, flashes the sign.\n\nBeginning in the early 1970s, the horns were known as the \"P-Funk sign\" to fans of [[Parliament-Funkadelic]]. It was used by [[George Clinton (musician)|George Clinton]] and [[Bootsy Collins]] as the password to the Mothership,<ref name=appleford>{{cite web |url=http://www.lacitybeat.com/article.php?id=1216&IssueNum=66 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071122030548/http://www.lacitybeat.com/article.php?id=1216&IssueNum=66 |archivedate=November 22, 2007 |title=Odyssey of the Devil Horns |first=Steve |last=Appleford |publisher=Los Angeles City Beat |date=September 9, 2004 |quote=A friend arranges a meeting with Clinton. I hand him a photograph of Dio making the hand signal, and tell him this is the man (or one of them) credited with bringing it to rock. Clinton stares at the picture for a long, silent minute, breathing heavily. Another minute passes. He's never heard of Ronnie James Dio. It's the P-Funk sign, man.}}</ref> a central element in Parliament's science-fiction [[P-Funk mythology|mythology]], and fans used it in return to show their enthusiasm for the band. Collins is depicted showing the P-Funk sign on the cover of his 1977 album ''[[Ahh... The Name Is Bootsy, Baby!]]''  \n\n[[Frank Zappa]] can be seen jokingly making the gesture in the 1979 film ''[[Baby Snakes]]'' in response to the audience, commenting, \"That's right, spindle twice.\"\n\nIn 1977, a painting<!-- animated painting??? --> of [[Gene Simmons]] (of the band [[Kiss (band)|KISS]]) exhibits the sign on the cover of ''[[Love Gun]]'', the band's sixth studio album. Simmons still utilizes the sign, both on and off stage.\n\n[[Marlon Brando]] makes the sign whilst singing \"[[Luck Be a Lady]]\" in the 1955 film ''[[Guys and Dolls (film)|Guys and Dolls]]'', seeming to indicate it was a sign for snake eyes in the craps game he is playing for the gamblers' souls.<ref>{{cite web|title=Marlon Brando-Luck Be a Lady|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=f-JzdRJCcsg|website=youtube.com|accessdate=13 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1985 film, ''The Breakfast Club'', Richard \"Dick\" Vernon is the grumpy vice principal of Shermer High School and the main antagonist of the film. One of his most famous lines is, \" Don't mess with the bull young man, you'll get the horns\", flashing the sign of the horns while rotating his wrist.\n\nIn one episode of the popular animated series [[The Simpsons]], a female tramp is seen warding off a male tramp using the sign of the horns using her thumbs and index fingers, screaming 'And you're a three-headed devil dog! Devil dog!'\n\nFor the 2016 Indian movie ''[[Rock On 2]]'', The \"2\" in the title is stylized with the sign of the horns, with the two extended fingers representing \"2\".\n\n===Heavy metal culture===\n[[File:Dio throwing Horns.jpg|thumb|Vocalist [[Ronnie James Dio]] making the sign at a [[Heaven & Hell (band)|Heaven and Hell]] concert in 2007. The gesture is quite common within [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] culture.]]\n\n[[Ronnie James Dio]] was known for popularizing the sign of the horns in [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]].<ref name=\"appleford\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/columns/junkyard/the_devils_horns_a_rock_and_roll_symbol.html |title=The Devil's Horns: A Rock And Roll Symbol |publisher=Ultimate-Guitar.com |date=September 7, 2005}}</ref> He claimed his Italian grandmother used it to ward off the [[evil eye]] (which is known in Southern Italy as ''[[Evil eye|malocchio]]''). Dio began using the sign soon after joining the metal band [[Black Sabbath]] in 1979. The previous singer in the band, [[Ozzy Osbourne]], was rather well known for using the [[V Sign|\"peace\"]] sign at concerts, raising the index and middle finger in the form of a V. Dio, in an attempt to connect with the fans, wanted to similarly use a hand gesture. However, not wanting to copy Osbourne, he chose to use the sign his grandmother always made.<ref>Ronnie James Dio interview in the 2005 documentary ''[[Metal: A Headbanger's Journey]]''. In the interview he also ridicules Gene Simmons for taking credit for originating use of the sign in heavy metal, attributing the claim to Simmons' well-known egotism.</ref> The horns became famous in metal concerts very soon after Black Sabbath's first tour with Dio. The sign would later be appropriated by heavy metal fans under the name \"maloik\", a corruption of the original ''malocchio''.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\n[[Geezer Butler|Terry \"Geezer\" Butler]] of Black Sabbath can be seen \"raising the horns\" in a photograph taken in 1971. The photograph is included in the CD booklet of the ''[[Symptom of the Universe: The Original Black Sabbath 1970\u20131978]]'' compilation album. This would indicate that there had been some association between the \"horns\" and heavy metal before Dio's popularization of it.\n\nWhen asked if he was the one who introduced the hand gesture to metal subculture, Dio said in a 2001 interview with Metal-Rules.com:\n\n{{quote|I doubt very much if I would be the first one who ever did that. That's like saying I invented the wheel, I'm sure someone did that at some other point. I think you'd have to say that I made it fashionable. I used it so much and all the time and it had become my trademark until the [[Britney Spears]] audience decided to do it as well. So it kind of lost its meaning with that. But it was \u2026 I was in Sabbath at the time. It was a symbol that I thought was reflective of what that band was supposed to be all about. It's NOT the devil's sign like we're here with the devil. It's an Italian thing I got from my Grandmother called the \"Malocchio\". It's to ward off the Evil Eye or to give the Evil Eye, depending on which way you do it. It's just a symbol but it had magical incantations and attitudes to it and I felt it worked very well with Sabbath. So I became very noted for it and then everybody else started to pick up on it and away it went. But I would never say I take credit for being the first to do it. I say because I did it so much that it became the symbol of rock and roll of some kind.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metal-rules.com/zine/index.php?option=content&task=view&id=666 |title=Dio - Interviewed By EvilG |publisher=Metal-Rules.com |date=March 9, 2001}}</ref>}}\n\n[[Gene Simmons]] of the rock group [[Kiss (band)|KISS]] attempted to claim the \"devil horns\" hand gesture for his own. According to CBS News, \"Simmons filed an application on Friday, June 16, 2017 with the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office for a trademark on the hand gesture he regularly uses during concerts and public appearances \u2014 thumb, index and pinky fingers extended, with the middle and ring fingers folded down. According to Simmons, this hand gesture was first used in commerce\u00a0\u2014\u00a0by him\u00a0\u2014\u00a0on Nov. 14, 1974. He is claiming the hand gesture should be trademarked for \"entertainment, namely live performances by a musical artist [and] personal appearances by a musical artist.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/gene-simmons-trademark-devil-horns-hand-gesture/|title=Gene Simmons wants to trademark \u201cdevil horns\u201d hand gesture|publisher=CBS News|date=June 15, 2017}}</ref> Simmons abandoned this application on June 21, 2017.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/legalentertainment/2017/06/21/breaking-gene-simmons-abandons-hand-gesture-trademark-application/#77f2bc74faac|title=Gene Simmons Abandons Hand Gesture Trademark Application |magazine=Forbes |date=June 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Electronic communication===\nIn text-based electronic communication, the sign of the horns is represented with the <code>\\../</code>, <code>\\m/</code> or <code>|m|</code> emoticon and sometimes with <code>/../</code>. The [[Unicode]] character U+1F918 \ud83e\udd18 SIGN OF THE HORNS was introduced in Unicode 8.0 as an [[emoji]], on June 17, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2015/06/burrito-sign-of-the-horns-and-35-other-emoji-approved-in-unicode-8-0/|title=\u201cBurrito,\u201d \u201cSign Of The Horns,\u201d and 35 other emoji approved in Unicode 8.0|publisher=|accessdate=21 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Gang hand signal===\nThe \"sign of the horns\" hand gesture is used in [[criminal gang]] subcultures to indicate membership or affiliation with [[MS-13|Mara Salvatrucha]]. The significance is both the resemblance of an inverted \"devil horns\" to the Latin letter 'M', and in the broader demonic connotation, of fierceness and nonconformity.  \n[[File:Mara_Salvatrucha_MS13.jpg|thumbnail|An [[MS-13]] gang member displays \"sign of the horns\" gang sign]]\n\n===Sports culture===\n[[File:hookemhorns.jpg|thumbnail|A fan displays the Hook 'em Horns during a Texas football game versus Arkansas.]]\n\n[[Hook 'em Horns]] is the slogan and hand signal of the [[University of Texas at Austin]]. Students and alumni of the university employ a greeting consisting of the phrase \"Hook 'em\" or \"Hook 'em Horns\" and also use the phrase as a parting good-bye or as the closing line in a letter or story.  The [[gesture]] is meant to approximate the shape of the head and horns of the [[University of Texas at Austin|UT]] mascot, the [[Texas longhorn (cattle)|Texas Longhorn]] [[Bevo (mascot)|Bevo]].\n\nFans of the [[University of South Florida]] Bulls use the same hand sign at their athletic events, except that the hand is turned around and facing the other way.  With the middle and ring finger extending towards the person presenting the \"Go Bulls\" sign.\n\nFans of [[North Dakota State University]] Bison athletics also use a similar hand gesture, known as \"Go Bison!\"  The pinky and index fingers are usually slightly bent, however, to mimic the shape of a [[bison]]'s horns.\n\nFans of [[North Carolina State University]] Wolfpack athletics use a similar gesture with the middle and ring fingers moving up and down over the thumb to mimic a wolf's jaw.\n\nFans of  [[University of California, Irvine]] Anteaters use a similar sign with the middle and ring fingers out to resemble the head of the mighty anteater.\n\nFans of [[University of Nevada, Reno]] Wolf Pack athletics use a similar sign with the middle and ring fingers out to resemble the wolf's snout. \n\nA variation of this hand gesture is also used in the [[professional wrestling]] industry, which fans dub the \"Too Sweet\". It was possibly innovated by [[Scott Hall]] and the other members of [[The Kliq]], and has since been attributed to other wrestling groups such as [[New World Order (professional wrestling)|the nWo]] and [[Bullet Club]], as well as individual wrestlers such as [[Finn B\u00e1lor]].\n\nFans of [[University of Utah]] athletics, particularly football and gymnastics, use a gesture where the index and pinky finger are straight and parallel to each other, forming a block \"U.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alumni.utah.edu/muss/membership/ |title=MUSS - Student Cheer Section for the U of U Utes - University of Utah Alumni Association &#124; MUSS |publisher=Alumni.utah.edu |date=2011-03-18 |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref>\n\nFans of [[Northwestern State University]] Demon athletics also use a similar hand gesture, known as \"Fork 'em!\"  The pinky and index fingers are extended but a little more parallel to each other resembling the horns on a demon.\n\n[[Arizona State University]] [[Sun Devil]] fans make a pitchfork sign by extending the index and middle fingers, as well as the pinky. The thumb holds down the ring finger to complete the gesture.\n\nFans of the [[Wichita State University]] Shockers frequently hold up their middle finger in addition to the pointer and pinky fingers as a reference to the [[Shocker (hand gesture)|comic sexual act]].\n\nFans of the [[Grand Canyon University]] Antelopes use this hand gesture with a slight variation by touching the tips of the ring and middle finger with the thumb to form the shape of an antelope and its horns. Often followed by the phrase \"Lopes up\".\n\nFans of the [[Universidad de Chile]] soccer team use this gesture to represent their support for the team by forming a U-shaped hand gesture, often followed by the phrase \"Grande la U\".\n\n== See also ==\n* [[ILY sign]] is sometimes confused with this gesture because many users tend to do the \"horns\" improperly by extending their thumb.\n* [[Shaka sign]]\n* [[Cornicello]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Sign of the horns}}\n*[http://www.rockandrollconfidential.com/archives/archives_death.php Rock and Roll Confidential on their logo]\n*{{cite magazine |url=http://www.chartattack.com/news/31464/ronnie-james-dio-re-claims-the-devil-horns |first=Neil |last=Haverty |date=2002-05-30 |title=Ronnie James Dio Re-Claims the Devil Horns |magazine=[[Chart (magazine)|Chart]] |accessdate=2009-09-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091003114135/http://www.chartattack.com/news/31464/ronnie-james-dio-re-claims-the-devil-horns |archivedate=2009-10-03 }}\n*[https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2005/01/images/20050120-1_p44294-227-515h.html President George W. Bush, gestures the \"Hook 'em, horns,\" the salute of the University of Texas Longhorns.(...)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071122030548/http://www.lacitybeat.com/article.php?id=1216&IssueNum=66 Odyssey of the Devil Horns: Who is responsible for bringing metal's famous hand signal to the tribe?] ''[[Los Angeles CityBeat]]'', Sept. 9, 2004\n\n{{Gestures}}\n{{Superstitions}}\n{{Rock festival}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sign Of The Horns}}\n[[Category:Hand gestures]]\n[[Category:Heavy metal subculture]]\n[[Category:Superstitions of Italy]]\n[[Category:Symbols]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean]]\n", "name_user": "MatthewHoobin", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOffensive gesture:Spacing.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sign_of_the_horns"}
{"title_page": "Acrocnida", "text_new": "{{short description|Genus of echinoderms}}\n{{italic title}}\n{{Taxobox\n| name            = Acrocnida\n| image           = Acrocnida semisquamata - Planche VIII (Koehler, 1914) (cropped).jpg\n| image_alt       = Several Acrocnida semisquamata\n| image_caption   = Acrocnida semisquamata - Planche VIII\n| regnum          = [[Animalia]]\n| phylum          = [[Echinodermata]]\n| classis         = [[Ophiuroidea]]\n| ordo            = [[Ophiurida]]\n| familia         = [[Amphiruridae]]\n| genus           = '''Arcocnida'''\n| genus_authority = Gisl\u00e9n, 1926\n}}\n\n'''''Acrocnida''''' is a genus of [[brittle star]]s in the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Amphiuridae]]. The genus contains three members: ''[[Acrocnida brachiata]], Acrocnida semisquamata,'' and ''Acrocnida spatulispina.'' There has also been observed hybridization between both ''[[Acrocnida brachiata]]'' and ''Acrocnida spatulispina''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Muths|first=D.|last2=Davoult|first2=D.|last3=Jolly|first3=M. T.|last4=Gentil|first4=F.|last5=Jollivet|first5=D.|date=June 2010|title=Pre-zygotic factors best explain reproductive isolation between the hybridizing species of brittle-stars Acrocnida brachiata and A. spatulispina (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea)|url=http://link.springer.com/10.1007/s10709-010-9441-4|journal=Genetica|language=en|volume=138|issue=6|pages=667\u2013679|doi=10.1007/s10709-010-9441-4|issn=0016-6707}}</ref>''.'' It is a fairly common genus, usually found along the coasts of Northwestern Europe, but with some species like semisquamata appearing around West Africa.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=St\u00f6hr|first=Sabine|last2=Muths|first2=Delphine|date=June 2010|title=Morphological diagnosis of the two genetic lineages of Acrocnida brachiata (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea), with description of a new species|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/journal-of-the-marine-biological-association-of-the-united-kingdom/article/morphological-diagnosis-of-the-two-genetic-lineages-of-acrocnida-brachiata-echinodermata-ophiuroidea-with-description-of-a-new-species/F604CF39D26AD16AFD1FBB185ADDB876|journal=Journal of the Marine Biological Association of the United Kingdom|language=en|volume=90|issue=4|pages=831\u2013843|doi=10.1017/S0025315409990749|issn=1469-7769}}</ref> Members of this genus primarily prefer intertidal and sub-tidal habitats, and they are they are less likely to be found in intertidal areas by comparison. This genus was not officially classified until 1926, by T. Gisl\u00e9n.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.marinespecies.org/aphia.php?p=taxdetails&id=236129|title=WoRMS - World Register of Marine Species - Acrocnida Gisl\u00e9n, 1926|website=www.marinespecies.org|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> One study found that due to the increased calcification that ''[[Acrocnida brachiata]]'' causes could be a potential source of Carbon Dioxide for not only the warm, shallow environments they live in, but also for the atmosphere.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Davoult|first=Dominique|last2=Harlay|first2=J\u00e9r\u00f4me|last3=Gentil|first3=Franck|date=November 2009|title=Contribution of a Dense Population of the Brittle Star Acrocnida brachiata (Montagu) to the Biogeochemical Fluxes of CO2 in a Temperate Coastal Ecosystem|url=http://link.springer.com/10.1007/s12237-009-9216-2|journal=Estuaries and Coasts|language=en|volume=32|issue=6|pages=1103\u20131110|doi=10.1007/s12237-009-9216-2|issn=1559-2723}}</ref>\n\n==Species==\nThe [[World Register of Marine Species]] lists the following species.<ref name=WoRMS>{{cite WoRMS |author=Saiz-Salinas, Jos\u00e9 |year=2018 |title=''Acrocnida'' Gisl\u00e9n, 1926 |id=236139 |accessdate=13 July 2018|db=}}</ref>\n\n* ''[[Acrocnida brachiata]]'' <small>(Montagu, 1804)</small>\n* ''[[Acrocnida semisquamata]]'' <small>(Koehler, 1914)</small>\n* ''[[Acrocnida spatulispina]]'' (<small>St\u00f6hr & Muths, 2010)</small>\n\n''The species, [[Acrocnida brachiata]],'' was recently found to be two species'', [[Acrocnida brachiata]]'' and ''[[Acrocnida semisquamata]], by St\u00f6hr & Muths in 2010.''\n\n== Distribution ==\nThis genus can be found spread around Northwestern Europe and off the Western coast of Africa. ''Acrocnida'' members generally prefer the sandy bottoms (specifically fine or muddy sand)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hammond|first=R.|date=|title=The echinoderms of Norfolk|url=|journal=THE NORFOLK & NORWICH|volume=29.1 (1991)|pages=33|via=}}</ref> of shallow coastal zones for their habitats.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Jangoux|first=Michel|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=BS_F4HfxRBAC&oi=fnd&pg=PA127&dq=acrocnida&ots=3XcTpq2QC-&sig=GHGMzG7hdPelZNNlYuKwrtdyfmA#v=onepage&q=acrocnida&f=false|title=Echinoderms: Present and Past|date=1980-06-01|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-90-6191-077-0|language=en}}</ref> ''Acrocnida brachiata'' is a fairly widespread member of this genus in terms of distribution. While it was discovered in 1808 by George Montagu,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Linnean Society of London.|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/13719|title=Transactions of the Linnean Society of London.|last2=London|first2=Linnean Society of|last3=London|first3=Linnean Society of|date=1808|publisher=[The Society], 1791-1875.|volume=v.9 (1808)|location=London :}}</ref> their spread was still being recorded as far as the 1970s, with it being found in the [[North Sea]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Boos|first=Karin|last2=Franke|first2=Heinz-Dieter|date=October 2006|title=Brittle stars (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea) in the German Bight (North Sea)\u2014species diversity during the past 130 years|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/product/identifier/S0025315406014184/type/journal_article|journal=Journal of the Marine Biological Association of the United Kingdom|language=en|volume=86|issue=5|pages=1187\u20131197|doi=10.1017/S0025315406014184|issn=0025-3154}}</ref> In recency, ''Acrocnida brachiata'' has been found in the [[Aegean Sea]] for the first time in 2007,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Koukouras|first=Athanasios|last2=Sinis|first2=Apostolos I.|last3=Bobori|first3=Dimitra|last4=Kazantzidis|first4=Savas|last5=Kitsos|first5=Miltiadis-Spyridon|date=2007|title=The echinoderm (Deuterostomia) fauna of the Aegean Sea, and comparison with those of the neighbouring seas|url=|journal=JOURNAL OF BIOLOGICAL RESEARCH-THESSALONIKI|volume=7|pages=67\u201392|via=}}</ref> after only being noted on the [[Mediterranean Sea]] facing coast of [[Turkey]] in 1995.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=\u00d6zaydin|first=O.|last2=Katagan|first2=T.|last3=\u00dcnsal|first3=S.|date=1995-05-05|title=THE ECHINODERMS OF THE TURKISH SEAS|url=https://brill.com/view/journals/ijee/41/1/article-p57_5.xml|journal=Israel Journal of Ecology and Evolution|language=en|volume=41|issue=1|pages=57\u201368|doi=10.1080/00212210.1995.10688778|issn=2224-4662}}</ref> ''Acrocnida semisquamata'' is primarily located off of the coast of [[Ghana]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.marinespecies.org/aphia.php?p=taxdetails&id=242617#distributions|title=WoRMS - World Register of Marine Species - Acrocnida semisquamata (Koehler, 1914)|website=www.marinespecies.org|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> and ''Acrocnida spatulispina'' has only been observed in the [[English Channel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.marinespecies.org/aphia.php?p=taxdetails&id=412703#distributions|title=WoRMS - World Register of Marine Species - Acrocnida spatulispina St\u00f6hr & Muths, 2010|website=www.marinespecies.org|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n== Morphology ==\n''Acrocnida'' follows the body plan of other ''[[Amphiuridae]],'' as they possess central disks surrounded by five long, thin arms. They only possess one outer mouth papilla, which is removed from the infradental papillae.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.marlin.ac.uk/species/detail/134|title=MarLIN - The Marine Life Information Network - Sand burrowing brittlestar (Acrocnida brachiata)|website=www.marlin.ac.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Members of ''Acrocnida'' possess mucous glands described as \"multecellular aggregations of pyriform cells with elongate necks\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buchanan|first=John B.|date=1963|title=Mucus Secretion Within the Spines of Ophiuroid Echinoderms|url=https://zslpublications.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1469-7998.1963.tb01611.x|journal=Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London|language=en|volume=141|issue=2|pages=251\u2013259|doi=10.1111/j.1469-7998.1963.tb01611.x|issn=1469-7998}}</ref> Like other members of ''[[Ophiurida]], Acrocnida'' can part with limbs and regenerate a new limb.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wilkie|first=I. C.|date=1978|title=Arm autotomy in brittlestars (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea)|url=https://zslpublications.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1469-7998.1978.tb03920.x|journal=Journal of Zoology|language=en|volume=186|issue=3|pages=311\u2013330|doi=10.1111/j.1469-7998.1978.tb03920.x|issn=1469-7998}}</ref>\n\n== Reproductive Cycle ==\nThese sea stars mainly follow an annual schedule for their reproductive cycle. Looking at ''Acrocnida brachiata'', gonads begin forming in late Summer and Autumn, with the spawning taking place within a range of March to May. This places ''Acrocnida brachiata'' and other members of the genus in the category of \"discreet annual breeder.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Jangoux|first=Michel|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=y6loLAkmv4QC&oi=fnd&pg=PA83&dq=acrocnida&ots=7vYBbTK039&sig=YHQ9CR3nk_b06L2pqyerytuepNM#v=onepage&q=acrocnida&f=false|title=Echinoderm Research|date=1990-06-01|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-90-6191-141-8|language=en}}</ref> Eggs created by ''Acrocnida brachiata'' lie in a range of 180 to 350 micrometers. This size places ''Acrocnida'' with an \"intermediate level of fecundity\"<ref name=\":0\" /> and a larval development similar to other genera of sea stars.\n\n== Common Behavior ==\n''Acrocnida'' and other ''[[Amphiuridae]]'' practice very similar behaviors. In order to avoid predation, these organisms dig a semi-permanent hole, which they reinforce using the mucus they naturally produce. They then dip their disk into the hole, and leave the arms just poking out enough so that they may still explore and interact with the area outside of their burrow. Members of the genus ''Acrocnida'' utilize their [[Water vascular system]] to ventilate their burrows.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Woodley|first=J. D.|date=1975-05-01|title=The behaviour of some amphiur1d Brittle-Stars|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022098175900143|journal=Journal of Experimental Marine Biology and Ecology|language=en|volume=18|issue=1|pages=29\u201346|doi=10.1016/0022-0981(75)90014-3|issn=0022-0981}}</ref> [[Acrocnida brachiata|''Acrocnida brachiata'']] is usually seen with [[Echinocardium cordatum|''Echinocardium cordatum'']], commonly known as the Sea Potato.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.marlin.ac.uk/species/detail/134|title=MarLIN - The Marine Life Information Network - Sand burrowing brittlestar (Acrocnida brachiata)|website=www.marlin.ac.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3468058}}\n\n[[Category:Ophiurida]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Genus of echinoderms}}\n{{italic title}}\n{{Taxobox\n| name = Acrocnida\n| image = [[File:Acrocnida semisquamata - Planche VIII (Koehler, 1914) (cropped).jpg|thumb|Acrocnida semisquamata - Planche VIII (Koehler, 1914) (cropped)]]\n| image_alt = Several Acrocnida semisquamata\n| image_caption = \n| regnum = [[Animalia]]\n| phylum = [[Echinodermata]]\n| classis = [[Ophiuroidea]]\n| ordo = [[Ophiurida]]\n| familia = [[Amphiruridae]]\n| genus = '''Arcocnida'''\n| genus_authority = Gisl\u00e9n, 1926\n}}\n\n'''''Acrocnida''''' is a genus of [[brittle star]]s in the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Amphiuridae]]. The genus contains three members: ''[[Acrocnida brachiata]], Acrocnida semisquamata,'' and ''Acrocnida spatulispina.'' There has also been observed hybridization between both ''[[Acrocnida brachiata]]'' and ''Acrocnida spatulispina''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Muths|first=D.|last2=Davoult|first2=D.|last3=Jolly|first3=M. T.|last4=Gentil|first4=F.|last5=Jollivet|first5=D.|date=June 2010|title=Pre-zygotic factors best explain reproductive isolation between the hybridizing species of brittle-stars Acrocnida brachiata and A. spatulispina (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea)|url=http://link.springer.com/10.1007/s10709-010-9441-4|journal=Genetica|language=en|volume=138|issue=6|pages=667\u2013679|doi=10.1007/s10709-010-9441-4|issn=0016-6707}}</ref>''.'' It is a fairly common genus, usually found along the coasts of Northwestern Europe, but with some species like semisquamata appearing around West Africa.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=St\u00f6hr|first=Sabine|last2=Muths|first2=Delphine|date=June 2010|title=Morphological diagnosis of the two genetic lineages of Acrocnida brachiata (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea), with description of a new species|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/journal-of-the-marine-biological-association-of-the-united-kingdom/article/morphological-diagnosis-of-the-two-genetic-lineages-of-acrocnida-brachiata-echinodermata-ophiuroidea-with-description-of-a-new-species/F604CF39D26AD16AFD1FBB185ADDB876|journal=Journal of the Marine Biological Association of the United Kingdom|language=en|volume=90|issue=4|pages=831\u2013843|doi=10.1017/S0025315409990749|issn=1469-7769}}</ref> Members of this genus primarily prefer intertidal and sub-tidal habitats, and they are they are less likely to be found in intertidal areas by comparison. This genus was not officially classified until 1926, by T. Gisl\u00e9n.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.marinespecies.org/aphia.php?p=taxdetails&id=236129|title=WoRMS - World Register of Marine Species - Acrocnida Gisl\u00e9n, 1926|website=www.marinespecies.org|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> One study found that due to the increased calcification that ''[[Acrocnida brachiata]]'' causes could be a potential source of Carbon Dioxide for not only the warm, shallow environments they live in, but also for the atmosphere.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Davoult|first=Dominique|last2=Harlay|first2=J\u00e9r\u00f4me|last3=Gentil|first3=Franck|date=November 2009|title=Contribution of a Dense Population of the Brittle Star Acrocnida brachiata (Montagu) to the Biogeochemical Fluxes of CO2 in a Temperate Coastal Ecosystem|url=http://link.springer.com/10.1007/s12237-009-9216-2|journal=Estuaries and Coasts|language=en|volume=32|issue=6|pages=1103\u20131110|doi=10.1007/s12237-009-9216-2|issn=1559-2723}}</ref>\n\n==Species==\nThe [[World Register of Marine Species]] lists the following species.<ref name=WoRMS>{{cite WoRMS |author=Saiz-Salinas, Jos\u00e9 |year=2018 |title=''Acrocnida'' Gisl\u00e9n, 1926 |id=236139 |accessdate=13 July 2018|db=}}</ref>\n\n* ''[[Acrocnida brachiata]]'' <small>(Montagu, 1804)</small>\n* ''[[Acrocnida semisquamata]]'' <small>(Koehler, 1914)</small>\n* ''[[Acrocnida spatulispina]]'' (<small>St\u00f6hr & Muths, 2010)</small>\n\n''The species, [[Acrocnida brachiata]],'' was recently found to be two species'', [[Acrocnida brachiata]]'' and ''[[Acrocnida semisquamata]], by St\u00f6hr & Muths in 2010.''\n\n== Distribution ==\nThis genus can be found spread around Northwestern Europe and off the Western coast of Africa. ''Acrocnida'' members generally prefer the sandy bottoms (specifically fine or muddy sand)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hammond|first=R.|date=|title=The echinoderms of Norfolk|url=|journal=THE NORFOLK & NORWICH|volume=29.1 (1991)|pages=33|via=}}</ref> of shallow coastal zones for their habitats.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Jangoux|first=Michel|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=BS_F4HfxRBAC&oi=fnd&pg=PA127&dq=acrocnida&ots=3XcTpq2QC-&sig=GHGMzG7hdPelZNNlYuKwrtdyfmA#v=onepage&q=acrocnida&f=false|title=Echinoderms: Present and Past|date=1980-06-01|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-90-6191-077-0|language=en}}</ref> ''Acrocnida brachiata'' is a fairly widespread member of this genus in terms of distribution. While it was discovered in 1808 by George Montagu,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Linnean Society of London.|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/13719|title=Transactions of the Linnean Society of London.|last2=London|first2=Linnean Society of|last3=London|first3=Linnean Society of|date=1808|publisher=[The Society], 1791-1875.|volume=v.9 (1808)|location=London :}}</ref> their spread was still being recorded as far as the 1970s, with it being found in the [[North Sea]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Boos|first=Karin|last2=Franke|first2=Heinz-Dieter|date=October 2006|title=Brittle stars (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea) in the German Bight (North Sea)\u2014species diversity during the past 130 years|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/product/identifier/S0025315406014184/type/journal_article|journal=Journal of the Marine Biological Association of the United Kingdom|language=en|volume=86|issue=5|pages=1187\u20131197|doi=10.1017/S0025315406014184|issn=0025-3154}}</ref> In recency, ''Acrocnida brachiata'' has been found in the [[Aegean Sea]] for the first time in 2007,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Koukouras|first=Athanasios|last2=Sinis|first2=Apostolos I.|last3=Bobori|first3=Dimitra|last4=Kazantzidis|first4=Savas|last5=Kitsos|first5=Miltiadis-Spyridon|date=2007|title=The echinoderm (Deuterostomia) fauna of the Aegean Sea, and comparison with those of the neighbouring seas|url=|journal=JOURNAL OF BIOLOGICAL RESEARCH-THESSALONIKI|volume=7|pages=67\u201392|via=}}</ref> after only being noted on the [[Mediterranean Sea]] facing coast of [[Turkey]] in 1995.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=\u00d6zaydin|first=O.|last2=Katagan|first2=T.|last3=\u00dcnsal|first3=S.|date=1995-05-05|title=THE ECHINODERMS OF THE TURKISH SEAS|url=https://brill.com/view/journals/ijee/41/1/article-p57_5.xml|journal=Israel Journal of Ecology and Evolution|language=en|volume=41|issue=1|pages=57\u201368|doi=10.1080/00212210.1995.10688778|issn=2224-4662}}</ref> ''Acrocnida semisquamata'' is primarily located off of the coast of [[Ghana]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.marinespecies.org/aphia.php?p=taxdetails&id=242617#distributions|title=WoRMS - World Register of Marine Species - Acrocnida semisquamata (Koehler, 1914)|website=www.marinespecies.org|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> and ''Acrocnida spatulispina'' has only been observed in the [[English Channel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.marinespecies.org/aphia.php?p=taxdetails&id=412703#distributions|title=WoRMS - World Register of Marine Species - Acrocnida spatulispina St\u00f6hr & Muths, 2010|website=www.marinespecies.org|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n== Morphology ==\n''Acrocnida'' follows the body plan of other ''[[Amphiuridae]],'' as they possess central disks surrounded by five long, thin arms. They only possess one outer mouth papilla, which is removed from the infradental papillae.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.marlin.ac.uk/species/detail/134|title=MarLIN - The Marine Life Information Network - Sand burrowing brittlestar (Acrocnida brachiata)|website=www.marlin.ac.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Members of ''Acrocnida'' possess mucous glands described as \"multecellular aggregations of pyriform cells with elongate necks\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buchanan|first=John B.|date=1963|title=Mucus Secretion Within the Spines of Ophiuroid Echinoderms|url=https://zslpublications.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1469-7998.1963.tb01611.x|journal=Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London|language=en|volume=141|issue=2|pages=251\u2013259|doi=10.1111/j.1469-7998.1963.tb01611.x|issn=1469-7998}}</ref> Like other members of ''[[Ophiurida]], Acrocnida'' can part with limbs and regenerate a new limb.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wilkie|first=I. C.|date=1978|title=Arm autotomy in brittlestars (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea)|url=https://zslpublications.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1469-7998.1978.tb03920.x|journal=Journal of Zoology|language=en|volume=186|issue=3|pages=311\u2013330|doi=10.1111/j.1469-7998.1978.tb03920.x|issn=1469-7998}}</ref>\n\n== Reproductive Cycle ==\nThese sea stars mainly follow an annual schedule for their reproductive cycle. Looking at ''Acrocnida brachiata'', gonads begin forming in late Summer and Autumn, with the spawning taking place within a range of March to May. This places ''Acrocnida brachiata'' and other members of the genus in the category of \"discreet annual breeder.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Jangoux|first=Michel|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=y6loLAkmv4QC&oi=fnd&pg=PA83&dq=acrocnida&ots=7vYBbTK039&sig=YHQ9CR3nk_b06L2pqyerytuepNM#v=onepage&q=acrocnida&f=false|title=Echinoderm Research|date=1990-06-01|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-90-6191-141-8|language=en}}</ref> Eggs created by ''Acrocnida brachiata'' lie in a range of 180 to 350 micrometers. This size places ''Acrocnida'' with an \"intermediate level of fecundity\"<ref name=\":0\" /> and a larval development similar to other genera of sea stars.\n\n== Common Behavior ==\n''Acrocnida'' and other ''[[Amphiuridae]]'' practice very similar behaviors. In order to avoid predation, these organisms dig a semi-permanent hole, which they reinforce using the mucus they naturally produce. They then dip their disk into the hole, and leave the arms just poking out enough so that they may still explore and interact with the area outside of their burrow. Members of the genus ''Acrocnida'' utilize their [[Water vascular system]] to ventilate their burrows.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Woodley|first=J. D.|date=1975-05-01|title=The behaviour of some amphiur1d Brittle-Stars|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022098175900143|journal=Journal of Experimental Marine Biology and Ecology|language=en|volume=18|issue=1|pages=29\u201346|doi=10.1016/0022-0981(75)90014-3|issn=0022-0981}}</ref> [[Acrocnida brachiata|''Acrocnida brachiata'']] is usually seen with [[Echinocardium cordatum|''Echinocardium cordatum'']], commonly known as the Sea Potato.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.marlin.ac.uk/species/detail/134|title=MarLIN - The Marine Life Information Network - Sand burrowing brittlestar (Acrocnida brachiata)|website=www.marlin.ac.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3468058}}\n\n[[Category:Ophiurida]]\n", "name_user": "MB", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix infobox image syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acrocnida"}
{"title_page": "Sarojini Pillay", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2018}}\n'''Sarojini [[Pillay]]''' is a [[Fiji]]an academic of [[India]]n descent.  In the second week of February 2006, Pillay, a former Registrar of the [[University of the South Pacific]] (USP), was appointed as the first Registrar of the newly founded [[University of Fiji]], scheduled to take up her duties on 13 March.\n\nPillay is a graduate of the [[Central Michigan University]] in the [[United States]], the [[University of Madras]] in India, and the [[Fiji School of Agriculture]].  She first became Registrar of the USP in 1991, and after her retirement from this position she was approached by the new university to be its first Registrar.\n\n== Sources ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060209150634/http://www.sun.com.fj/ Fiji Sun]\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pillay, Sarojini}}\n[[Category:Central Michigan University alumni]]\n[[Category:Fijian Hindus|Pillay, Sarojini]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Fijian Tamils]]\n[[Category:University of the South Pacific faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Madras alumni]]\n[[Category:Women academic administrators]]\n[[Category:Indian academic administrators]]\n[[Category:Fijian women]]\n[[Category:Fijian women academics]]\n[[Category:Fijian academic administrators]]\n[[Category:21st-century Fijian educators]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Fiji-bio-stub}}\n{{Academic-administrator-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2018}}\n'''Sarojini [[Pillay]]''' is a [[Fiji]]an academic of [[India]]n descent.  In the second week of February 2006, Pillay, a former Registrar of the [[University of the South Pacific]] (USP), was appointed as the first Registrar of the newly founded [[University of Fiji]], scheduled to take up her duties on 13 March.\n\nPillay is a graduate of the [[Central Michigan University]] in the [[United States]], the [[University of Madras]] in India, and the [[Fiji School of Agriculture]].  She first became Registrar of the USP in 1991, and after her retirement from this position she was approached by the new university to be its first Registrar.\n\n== Sources ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060209150634/http://www.sun.com.fj/ Fiji Sun]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pillay, Sarojini}}\n[[Category:Central Michigan University alumni]]\n[[Category:Fijian Hindus|Pillay, Sarojini]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Fijian Tamils]]\n[[Category:University of the South Pacific faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Madras alumni]]\n[[Category:Women academic administrators]]\n[[Category:Indian academic administrators]]\n[[Category:Fijian women]]\n[[Category:Fijian women academics]]\n[[Category:Fijian academic administrators]]\n[[Category:21st-century Fijian educators]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Fiji-bio-stub}}\n{{Academic-administrator-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSources:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sarojini_Pillay"}
